  <subsection>
    <title>Cohomology</title>
    <p>
      We insert a remark here which we will build upon later.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <p>
        For <m>X \in \CSet, M \in \Ab</m>, define <m>H^i(X, M) := \Ext^i_{\CAb}(\ZZ[X], M)</m> viewing <m>M</m> as a discrete object in <m>\CAb</m>.
      </p>
    </definition>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        For <m>X \in \Top</m> a CW complex, <m>H^i(X, M)</m> is canonically identified with <m>H^i_{\sing}(X, M)</m>,
        the singular cohomology with coefficients in <m>M</m>.
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          This is a form of the Dold<ndash/>Thom theorem;
          see <xref ref="bib-Clausen-Scholze-notes"/>, Lecture 3 (but this is written with <m>\kappa</m> large).
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
    <remark xml:id="rem-profinite-projective">
      <p>
        Let <m>Z \to Y</m> be a surjection (in the sense of topological spaces) in <m>\Prof</m>.
        Per <xref ref="rem-change-pro-system-to-sequential"/>, we may write <m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m> as sequential inverse limits of finite sets:
        <m>Y = \varprojlim_{n \in \NN} Y_n</m>, <m>Z = \varprojlim_{n \in \NN} Z_n</m>.
        By renumbering as needed, we may express the surjection <m>Z \to Y</m> as a coherent sequence of surjective maps <m>Z_n \to Y_n</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        By <xref ref="rem-Stone-duality"/>, we can ensure than the transition maps in each system are surjective.
        However, we can actually do better: we can enforce that the maps
        <me>
          Z_{n+1} \to Z_n \times_{Y_n} Y_{n+1}
        </me>
        are surjective. To see this, we interpret <m>Y_n</m> and <m>Z_n</m> as coverings of <m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m>, respectively,
        by finite disjoint unions of closed-open subsets. We can then choose <m>Z_{n+1}</m> (and everything above it) so that as a covering, it
        refines not only <m>Z_n</m> but also the pullback cover from <m>Y_{n+1}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Using this, it is easy to see that any object of <m>\Prof</m> is projective: that is, given any <m>X \in \Prof</m>
        and any surjection <m>Z \to Y</m> in <m>\Prof</m>, any morphism <m>X \to Y</m> can be lifted through <m>Z</m>.
        In particular, any surjection <m>Y \to X</m> in <m>\Prof</m> admits a section; this is quite a special feature of the category
        (for instance it is totally false in <m>\CHaus</m>).
      </p>
      <p>
        It formally follows that any object of <m>\Prof</m> is also projective in <m>\CSet</m>.
        To wit, for <m>X \in \Prof</m> and <m>T \to S</m> a surjection in <m>\CSet</m>, the map <m>T(X) \to S(X)</m> is <em>a priori</em> not surjective,
        but we do know that every element of <m>S(X)</m> lifts to <m>T(Y)</m> for some surjection <m>Y \to X</m> in <m>\Prof</m> depending on the original element.
        
      </p>
    </remark>

    <remark xml:id="rem-minimal-covers-of-Ninfty">
      <p>
        We record an important special property of the space <m>\NN_\infty</m> used in <xref ref="prop-internally-projective"/>:
        given any surjection <m>S \to \NN_\infty</m> in <m>\Prof</m>, we can construct a closed subspace <m>S'</m> of <m>S</m>
        such that the composition <m>S' \to S \to \NN_\infty</m> is surjective and also bijective over <m>\NN</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Specifically, we take <m>S'</m> to be the union of the whole fiber over <m>\infty</m> plus a single lift of each <m>n \in \NN</m>.
        To see that this is closed in <m>S</m>, we check that the complement is open: each fiber of <m>S</m> over <m>n \in \NN</m> is itself open
        by continuity of <m>S \to \NN_\infty</m>, and the complement of a single point in this fiber is also open.
      </p>
    </remark>
  <subsection>
    <title>Six functors formalism for quasicoherent sheaves</title>
    <p>
      One takeaway from <xref ref="exa-base-extension-not-flat"/> is that we cannot rely on flatness of localization if we want to
      pass from solid modules to an associated theory of solid quasicoherent sheaves on schemes.
      This means that we have to give up on working exclusively with the category of solid modules and instead pass to its associated derived category.
      This is perhaps not surprising in light of the fact that we built some duality into the definition of solid modules,
      and duality is invariably a property about derived categories of modules anyway.
    </p>
    <p>
      In fact, there is already a similar issue with working with quasicoherent sheaves in scheme theory!
      if <m>f\colon Y \to X</m> is a morphism of schemes and <m>\calF</m> is a quasicoherent sheaf on <m>Y</m>, then we cannot
      guarantee that the direct image sheaf <m>f_* \calF</m> is actually quasicoherent unless the map <m>f</m> is <term>qcqs</term>,
      short for <term>quasicompact and quasiseparated</term> (<xref ref="bib-Stacks"/>, Tag 01LC).
      OTherwise, one is forced to take an infinite product of quasicoherent sheaves and this is not quasicoherent because
      <me>
        \left( \prod_i M_i \right) \otimes_R R[1/f] \neq \prod_i (M_i \otimes_R R[1/f]).
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      One can resolve both issues at once by working with the derived category of solid quasicoherent sheaves.
      In fact, in this context one can build a <term>six functors formalism</term> for quasicoherent sheaves
      analogous to what we are used to in etale cohomology!
      We will not focus on this right now, but it should become clear how to do this by the end of the course.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <biblio type="raw" xml:id="bib-Banus-Xarles">
    D. Rodríguez Banús and X. Xarles, <articletitle>Condensed sets via free resolutions</articletitle>, <url>https://arxiv.org/pdf/2209.01660</url> <year>2022</year>.
  </biblio>




  <subsection>
    <title>Setting up a comparison of solidifications</title>
    <p>
      Since we already know from <xref ref="lem-delta-pullback-on-Rhom"/> and <xref ref="prop-solid-category"/>
      that <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ} \in \CAb_\solid</m>,
      the key remaining point in constructing a functor <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid} \to \CAb_\solid</m> is to match up endomorphisms into and especially
      out of infinite products of <m>\ZZ_{\solid}</m> versus <m>\underline{\ZZ}</m>.
      We study these in <m>\CAb</m> using the object <m>P</m> over which we have already established some control;
      in the process, we will also identify its solidification.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <p>
        For each <m>n \in \NN</m>, we define the <m>n</m>-th coordinate map <m>c_n\colon P \to \underline{\ZZ}</m>.
        This is induced by the map <m>\ZZ[\underline{\NN_\infty}] \to \underline{\ZZ}</m> corresponding to the map <m>\NN_\infty \to \ZZ</m> in <m>\Prof</m>
        carrying <m>n</m> to 1 and all other elements to 0.
      </p>
      <p>
        The product of the maps <m>c_n</m> defines the full coordinate map <m>c \colon P \to \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m>,
        where the product is taken in <m>\CAb</m>. We may think of this product more concretely by first forming it in <m>\Top</m> and then applying the functor <m>\Top \to \CSet</m>.
      </p>
    </definition>
    <remark xml:id="rem-compare-homs-out-of-product-solid">
      <p>
        In order to match up <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ_\solid \in \Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m> with <m>\prod_n \underline{\ZZ} \in \CAb_\solid</m>, we need to know that
        <me>
          \Hom_{\CAb}\left( \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}, \underline{\ZZ} \right) = \bigoplus_\NN \ZZ.
        </me>
        There is an obvious map from right to left: each generator of the direct sum corresponds to the projection onto a single coordinate.
        However, we also obtain a map in the other direction by restricting along the coordinate map <m>c\colon P \to \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m>
        (<xref ref="rem-coord-map"/>) and then interpreting <m>\Hom_{\CAb}(P, \underline{\ZZ})</m> as the 
        null sequences in <m>\ZZ</m>, which is the same thing as the direct sum because <m>\ZZ</m> carries the discrete topology.
      </p>
      <p>
        It is clear that the composition from right to left to right is an isomorphism, but not so in the other direction:
        we do not have any formal control of morphisms out of a product in <m>\CAb</m> like we built into the construction of <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_{\solid}}</m>.
        To study the composition, we insert an additional term between <m>P</m> and <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> and use two different arguments
        to take the two steps across this intermediate term.
        This will amount to showing that <m>P</m> is <q>dense</q> in <m>\bigoplus_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m>, 
        or in more precise terms, the map <m>c_\solid\colon P_\solid \to \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> is an isomorphism (<xref ref="cor-solidification-of-P"/>).
      </p>
    </remark>
    <definition>
      <p>
        Note that <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> admits the subobject
        <me>
          \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} := \colim_{n \in \NN} \prod_\NN \underline{\{-n,\dots,n\}}.
        </me>
        In terms of evaluations at <m>S \in \Prof</m>, <m>\left(\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}\right)(S)</m> consists of continuous maps <m>S \to \prod_\NN \ZZ</m>,
        or equivalently families of continuous maps <m>S \to \ZZ</m> indexed by <m>\NN</m>. Each of these maps has bounded image, but
        <m>\left( \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \right)(S)</m> picks out the families with <em>uniformly</em> bounded image.
      </p>
      <p>
        From the explicit description of <m>\ZZ[\NN_\infty]</m> (<xref ref="exa-module-ring-topological-space"/>),
        we can factor <m>c\colon P \to \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> through <m>\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}</m> to yield a sequence of inclusions
        <men xml:id="eq-p-to-product">
          P \stackrel{c}{\to} \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \to \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}.
        </men>
        Namely, <m>\Hom_{\CAb}(P, \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}) = \prod_\NN \Hom_{\CAb}(P, \underline{\ZZ})</m> consists of infinite families of null sequences in <m>\ZZ</m>,
        while <m>\Hom_{\CAb}(P, \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ})</m> picks out those families whose images are uniformly bounded.
        The sequences corresponding to the factors of the map <m>c</m> only take values in <m>\{0,1\}</m>, so they form a family of the latter form.
      </p>
    </definition>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>A comparison of solidifications</title>
    <p>
      We now compare the effect of solidification across the terms of <xref ref="eq-p-to-product"/>.
      For the first step, the strategy is to build a diagram that allows us to exploit the fact that <m>\Delta\colon P \to P</m>
      becomes an isomorphism after solidification.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-diagram-for-Delta">
      <p>
        Let <m>\Delta\colon \ZZ[\NN] \to \ZZ[\NN]</m> denote the map <m>[n] \mapsto [n]-[n+1]</m>.
        We then obtain a commutative diagram
        <figure>
          <image>
            <latex-image>
              \xymatrix{
               \ZZ[\NN] \otimes \ZZ[\NN] \ar[r] \ar^{\Delta \otimes \id}[d]  &amp;\ZZ[\NN] \ar@{=}[d] \\
               \ZZ[\NN] \otimes \ZZ[\NN] \ar[r] &amp; \ZZ[\NN]
              }
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      of discrete abelian groups in which the top row arrow maps <m>[m] \otimes [n]</m> to <m>[n]</m> if <m>m = n</m> and 0 otherwise,
      and the bottom row maps <m>[m] \otimes [n]</m> to <m>[n]</m> if <m>m \leq n</m> and 0 otherwise.
      Note that the two rows are equalized by <m>\ZZ[\NN] \to \ZZ[\NN] \otimes \ZZ[\NN]</m> via <m>[n] \mapsto [n] \otimes [n]</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This promotes to a commutative diagram
        <figure>
          <image>
            <latex-image>
              \xymatrix{
                P \otimes P \ar[r] \ar^{\Delta \otimes \id}[d] &amp; P \ar@{=}[d] \\
                P \otimes P \ar[r] &amp; P
              }
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
        where again the rows are equalized by a map <m>P \to P \otimes P</m> acting via <m>[n] \mapsto [n] \otimes [n]</m>.
      </p>
    </definition>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-diagram-p-to-bd">
      <statement>
        <p>
          There exists a commutative diagram in <m>\CAb</m> of the form
          <figure>
            <image>
              <latex-image>
                \xymatrix{
                  P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \ar[r] \ar^{\Delta \otimes \id}[d] &amp; P \ar^{c}[d] \\
                  P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \ar[r] &amp; \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}
                }
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
          in which both rows are split surjections.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By tensoring the second diagram from <xref ref="def-diagram-for-Delta"/> on the right along <m>c</m>, 
          we get a diagram of the form we want except with <m>P</m> replaced by <m>\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}</m>.
          To get what we want, all that remains is to verify that the resulting top row
          <men xml:id="eq-Delta-top-row">
            P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \to \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}
          </men>
          factors through <m>c</m>; the splitting of the resulting top row will be guaranteed by the fact that since <m>c</m> is injective,  
           the composition <m>P \to P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \to P</m> will again be the identity.
        </p>
        <p>
          By Hom-tensor adjunction, we reinterpret <xref ref="eq-Delta-top-row"/> as an element of <m>\Hom_{\CAb}(P, \iHom_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ},\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}\right) </m>
          and in turn by <xref ref="rem-coord-map"/> as a null sequence in <m>\iHom_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ},\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}\right)</m>;
          the claim is that this sequence belongs to the image of
          <me> 
            \Hom_{\CAb}(P, \iHom_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ},P \right) 
          </me>
          under postcomposition with <m>c</m>; that just means that each individual term in the sequence belongs to <m>\iHom_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ},P \right)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The sequence in question is the one whose <m>n</m>-th term is the <m>n</m>-th projection <m>\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \to \underline{\ZZ}</m> followed
          by the <m>n</m>-th injection <m>\underline{\ZZ} \to \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}</m>. The latter is the image of <m>[n] \in P</m> under <m>c</m>, proving the claim.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-replace-bounded-with-P-solid">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The map <m>c_\solid\colon P_\solid \to \left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \right)_\solid</m> is an isomorphism in <m>\CAb</m>.
          Moreover, for each <m>i \gt 0</m>, <m>\iExt^i_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N\right) = 0</m> for all <m>N \in \CAb_{\solid}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We check the second assertion first.
          For the second assertion, we apply <m>\iExt^i(\bullet, N)</m> to the diagram in <xref ref="lem-diagram-p-to-bd"/> to obtain
          <figure>
            <image>
              <latex-image>
                \xymatrix{
                  \iExt^i_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N\right) \ar[r] \ar^{c^*}[d] &amp; \iExt^i_{\CAb}\left( P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N\right) \ar^{\Delta^* \otimes \id}[d] \\
                  \iExt^i_{\CAb}\left(P, N\right) \ar[r] &amp; \iExt^i_{\CAb}\left( P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N\right) 
                }
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
          where now both rows are split injections.
          By applying Hom-tensor adjunction to write
          <me>
            \iExt_{\CAb}^i\left( P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N\right) = \iExt^i_{\CAb}\left( P, \iHom_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N\right)\right)
          </me>
          and invoking <xref ref="prop-solid-category"/> to see that <m>\iHom_{\CAb}(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N)</m> is solid, we deduce that the
          right column is an isomorphism.
          Consequently, the upper composition is an injection, so we have an injection
          <me>
            \iExt^i_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N\right) \stackrel{c^*}{\to} \iExt^i_{\CAb}\left(P, N\right) = 0
          </me>
          where the right equality follows from <xref ref="prop-internally-projective"/>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the first assertion, we solidify the diagram in <xref ref="lem-diagram-p-to-bd"/> to obtain
          <figure>
            <image>
              <latex-image>
                \xymatrix{
                  \left(P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}\right)_\solid \ar[r] \ar^{\Delta \otimes \id}[d] &amp; P_\solid \ar^{c}[d] \\
                  \left(P \otimes \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}\right)_\solid \ar[r] &amp; \left( \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \right)_\solid
                }
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
          where now the bottom row is a split surjection. By considering the previous diagram with <m>i=0</m>, we see that the left column
          induces an isomorphism of representable functors and hence is an isomorphism by Yoneda's lemma.
          At this point we conclude that <m>c_\solid</m> is a split surjection; however, since the top row is also surjective,
          tracing clockwise from <m>\left( \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \right)_\solid</m> back to <m>P_\solid</m> yields a surjection whose postcomposition
          with <m>c_\solid</m> is the identity map. This proves that <m>c_\solid</m> is also injective.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <p>
      For the second step, we use a completely different strategy.
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="cor-replace-prod-with-bounded-solid">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The map <m>\left( \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \right)_\solid \to \left( \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ} \right)_\solid</m> is an isomorphism.
          Moreover, for each <m>i \gt 0</m>, the morphism <m>\iExt^i_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}, N\right) \to \iExt^i_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}, N\right)</m>
          is an isomorphism for all <m>N \in \CAb_{\solid}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By analogy with the construction of <m>\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}</m>, we define
          <me>
            \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\RR} := \colim_{n \in \NN} \prod_\NN \underline{[-n,n]};
          </me>
          we will construct an isomorphism
          <me>
            \left( \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}\right) / \left( \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \right) \cong \left( \prod_\NN \underline{\RR} \right) / \left( \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\RR} \right).
          </me>
          Since the right-hand side carries an evident <m>\underline{\RR}</m>-module structure, so does the left-hand side. 
          By <xref ref="cor-solid-R-module-is-zero-monomorphism"/>, this will yield the claim.
        </p>
        <p>
          The proposed isomorphism is formally equivalent to the claim that
          <me>
            \left( \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\RR} \right) / \left( \prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ} \right) \cong \left( \prod_\NN \underline{\RR} \right) / \left( \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ} \right);
          </me>
          this holds because <m>\RR/\ZZ</m> is compact.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-solidification-of-P">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The map <m>c_\solid \colon P_\solid \to \prod_{\NN} \underline{\ZZ}</m> is an isomorphism.
          (Note that the target is solid by <xref ref="lem-delta-pullback-on-Rhom"/> and <xref ref="prop-solid-category"/>.)
          Moreover, for each <m>i \gt 0</m>, <m>\iExt^i_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}, N\right) = 0</m> for all <m>N \in \CAb_{\solid}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          This follows by combining <xref ref="lem-replace-bounded-with-P-solid"/> and <xref ref="cor-replace-prod-with-bounded-solid"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>
    <p>
      We will use a similar idea to identify some more soldifications later; see <xref ref="lem-identify-solidification-of-free"/>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>From solid abelian groups to condensed abelian groups</title>
    <p>
      We now construct a functor from solid <m>\ZZ</m>-modules to solid objects in <m>\CAb</m>.
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-compare-hom-solid-con">
      <statement>
        In <m>\CAb</m>, for any at most countable index sets <m>I,J</m>, we have
        <me>
          \Hom_{\CAb}\left(\prod_I \underline{\ZZ}, \prod_J \underline{\ZZ}\right) = \prod_J \bigoplus_I \ZZ.
        </me>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We immediately reduce to the case where <m>I = \NN</m> and <m>J</m> is a singleton; that is, we must show that
          <me>
            R\Hom_{\CAb}\left(\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}, \underline{\ZZ}\right) = \bigoplus_\NN \ZZ.
          </me>
          By <xref ref="cor-solidification-of-P"/>, we may replace <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> with <m>P^\solid</m>;
          by adjunction, we may further replace <m>P^\solid</m> with <m>P</m>.
          This leaves us with the statement of <xref ref="lem-Rhom-P"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <proposition xml:id="thm-solid-to-condensed">
      <statement>
        <p>
          There is a fully faithful exact functor <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid} \to \CAb</m> carrying <m>\ZZ_\solid</m> to <m>\underline{\ZZ}</m> and compatible with
          all limits (notably countable products) and colimits.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="lem-compare-hom-solid-con"/>, we get a fully faithful functor <m>\ZZ_\solid \to \CAb</m> carrying <m>\prod_I \ZZ_\solid</m> to <m>\prod_I \underline{\ZZ}</m>.
          Since <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ_\solid</m> is a compact generator of <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m>, we get the functor we want by forming a left Kan extension.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
    <remark>
      <p>
        We note in passing that <xref ref="thm-solid-to-condensed"/> admits the following compatibility with solidification:
        applying the solidification functor <m>\Mod_\ZZ \to \Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m> and then passing to <m>\CAb</m> gives the same result as 
        passing from <m>\Mod_\ZZ</m> to <m>\CAb</m> (i.e., passing to discrete topological groups) and then solidifying in <m>\CAb</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>A characterization of solid condensed abelian groups</title>
    <p>
      It still remains to identify the essential image of the functor from solid <m>\ZZ</m>-modules.
      In one direction, it is easy to see that we get solid objects in <m>\CAb</m>.
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-solid-to-solid">
      <statement>
        The image of any <m>M \in \Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m> in <m>\CAb</m> is solid.
      </statement>
      <proof>
        For <m>M = \prod_I \ZZ_\solid</m> this follows from <xref ref="lem-delta-pullback-on-Rhom"/> and <xref ref="prop-solid-category"/>.
        Since <m>M</m> is a compact generator of <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m>, this is enough to deduce the full claim.
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <p>
      To go in the other direction, we must calculate some more solidifications using a process similar to the computation of <m>P_\solid</m>.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-construct-map-P-to-monoid">
      <p>
        For <m>S \in \Prof</m> infinite, we construct a morphism <m>g\colon P \to \ZZ[\underline{S}]</m> as follows.
        Per <xref ref="rem-change-pro-system-to-sequential"/>, we may write <m>S</m> as a sequential inverse limit of finite sets with surjective transition maps:
        <m>S = \varprojlim_{n \in \NN} S_n</m>.
        We inductively choose subsets <m>T_n \subset S_n</m> and maps <m>i_n: T_n \to S</m> subject to the following conditions:
        <ul>
          <li>
            Each composition <m>T_n \stackrel{i_n}{\to} S \to S_n</m> coincides with the inclusion <m>T_n \subseteq S_n</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            Each <m>T_n</m> is the complement of the images of the maps <m>T_m \stackrel{i_m}{\to} S \to S_n</m> for all <m>m \lt n</m>.
            In particular, <m>T_1 = S_1</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
        Choose a bijection <m>\NN \cong T_1 \sqcup T_2 \sqcup \cdots</m>.
        We then define the map <m>g\colon P \to \ZZ[\underline{S}]</m> by mapping each <m>T_n</m> via <m>i_m</m> minus the map given by taking <m>T_n \to S_{n-1}</m>
        and then collating the maps <m>i_m</m> for <m>m \lt n</m>. (That is, each element of <m>S_{n-1}</m> projects to <m>T_m</m> for a unique choice of <m>m</m>,
        and then we apply <m>i_m</m> for that choice of <m>m</m>.)
      </p>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <p>
        For <m>S = \NN_\infty</m>, in <xref ref="def-construct-map-P-to-monoid"/> we may take <m>T_n = \{n\}</m>.
        In this case, the resulting map <m>g</m> is nothing but the splitting of <m>\ZZ[\underline{\NN_\infty}] \to P</m> described in <xref ref="def-internally-projective-object"/>.
      </p>
    </remark>
        <p>
          We next follow the strategy of <xref ref="lem-diagram-p-to-bd"/>,
          except with no analogue of replacing <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> with <m>\prod_\NN^{\bd} \underline{\ZZ}</m>
          because <m>\ZZ[\underline{S}]</m> is already a colimit over compact subspaces (<xref ref="exa-module-ring-topological-space"/>).
        </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-identify-solidification-of-free">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any infinite <m>S \in \Prof</m> and any morphism <m>g\colon P \to \ZZ[\underline{S}]</m>
          constructed as in <xref ref="def-construct-map-P-to-monoid"/>, the induced map <m>g_\solid: P_\solid \cong \ZZ[\underline{S}]_\solid</m> is an isomorphism.
          Consequently, by <xref ref="cor-solidification-of-P"/> we obtain an isomorphism <m>\ZZ[\underline{S}]_\solid \cong \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We construct a diagram
          <figure>
            <image>
              <latex-image>
                \xymatrix{
                  P \otimes \ZZ[\underline{S}] \ar[r] \ar^{\Delta \otimes \id}[d] &amp; P \ar^{g}[d] \\
                  P \otimes \ZZ[\underline{S}] \ar[r] &amp; \ZZ[\underline{S}]
                }
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
          in which the bottom row is a split surjection. The bottom row corresponds to the null sequence of maps <m>\ZZ[\underline{S}] \to \ZZ[\underline{S}]</m>
          obtained by starting with the identity and successively subtracting off the compositions <m>S \to S_n \to S</m>
          (where the second map is the collated map from earlier).
          Then we argue as in <xref ref="lem-diagram-p-to-bd"/> to show that the lower composition factors through <m>g</m>;
          the left column becomes an isomorphism after solidifying; and tracing a loop clockwise from <m>P_\solid</m> in the solidified diagram yields an isomorphism.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <theorem xml:id="prop-solid-vs-presumptively-solid">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The object <m>M \in \CAb</m> is solid if and only if it belongs to the essential image of the functor <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid} \to \CAb</m>
          described in <xref ref="thm-solid-to-condensed"/>.
          In other words, we have an equivalence <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid} \cong \CAb_\solid</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="lem-solid-to-solid"/>, any object in the essential image is solid.
          Conversely, by <xref ref="lem-identify-solidification-of-free"/>,
          <m>\CAb_\solid</m> admits <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> as a single compact generator,
          so we can identify any object as a colimit of a diagram arising from <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
    <remark>
      <p>
        <xref ref="prop-solid-vs-presumptively-solid"/> has the effect that we can replace the study of <m>\CAb_\solid</m>
        with the equivalent but conceptually simpler category <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m>, whose definition contains no topology.
        One can also go in the opposite direction, as in the following.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <remark xml:id="rem-hom-from-torsion-vanishes-condensed">
      <p>
        We give an alternate proof of <xref ref="lem-hom-from-torsion-vanishes"/> in the setting of condensed abelian groups.
        In this language, the statement is that for <m>Q</m> a torsion <m>\ZZ</m>-module,
        <m>\iHom_{\CAb}(\underline{\QQ}, \underline{ZZ}) = 0</m>. To prove this, evaluate at <m>S \in \Prof</m>:
        <me>
          \iHom_{\CAb}(\underline{Q}, \underline{\ZZ})(S) = \Hom_{\CAb}(\underline{Q} \otimes \ZZ[\underline{S}], \underline{\ZZ})
          = \Hom_{\CAb}(\underline{Q}, \iHom_{\CAb}(\ZZ[\underline{S}], \underline{\ZZ})).
        </me>
        In this expression, <m>\iHom_{\CAb}(\ZZ[\underline{S}], \underline{\ZZ})</m> is represented by the locally compact topological abelian group
        consisting of the continuous (i.e., locally constant) functions <m>S \to \ZZ</m>, and we can interpret the outer <m>\Hom</m> in the category of topological abelian groups.
        But even at the level of underlying abelian groups this Hom is zero because <m>Q</m> cannot admit a nonzero map to any torsion-free abelian group.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

    <remark>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Since we already know from <xref ref="lem-delta-pullback-on-Rhom"/> and <xref ref="prop-solid-category"/>
      that <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ} \in \CAb_\solid</m>,
      the key remaining point in constructing a functor <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid} \to \CAb_\solid</m> is to match up endomorphisms into and especially
      out of infinite products of <m>\ZZ_{\solid}</m> versus <m>\underline{\ZZ}</m>.
      We study these in <m>\CAb</m> using the object <m>P</m> over which we have already established some control;
      in the process, we will also identify its solidification.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem-compare-homs-out-of-product-solid">
      <p>
        In order to match up <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ_\solid \in \Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m> with <m>\prod_n \underline{\ZZ} \in \CAb_\solid</m>, we need to know that
        <me>
          \Hom_{\CAb}\left( \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}, \underline{\ZZ} \right) = \bigoplus_\NN \ZZ.
        </me>
        There is an obvious map from right to left: each generator of the direct sum corresponds to the projection onto a single coordinate.
        However, we also obtain a map in the other direction by restricting along the coordinate map <m>c\colon P \to \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m>
        (<xref ref="rem-coord-map"/>) and then interpreting <m>\Hom_{\CAb}(P, \underline{\ZZ})</m> as the 
        null sequences in <m>\ZZ</m>, which is the same thing as the direct sum because <m>\ZZ</m> carries the discrete topology.
      </p>
      <p>
        It is clear that the composition from right to left to right is an isomorphism, but not so in the other direction:
        we do not have any formal control of morphisms out of a product in <m>\CAb</m> like we built into the construction of <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_{\solid}}</m>.
        To study the composition, we insert an additional term between <m>P</m> and <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> and use two different arguments
        to take the two steps across this intermediate term.
        This will amount to showing that <m>P</m> is <q>dense</q> in <m>\bigoplus_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m>, 
        or in more precise terms, the map <m>c_\solid\colon P_\solid \to \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> is an isomorphism (<xref ref="cor-solidification-of-P"/>).
      </p>
      <p>
        Note that both <m>P</m> and <m>\bigoplus_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> are sequential topological abelian groups,
        so we can interpret <m>c</m> as an inclusion in that category instead. The same will be true of the intermediate object we
        insert between them in <xref ref="def-strict-factorization"/>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Unfortunately, it is not straightforward to compare <m>P</m> with <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ_\solid</m>
      due to a subtle topological point which we now discuss and work around.
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-functor-sequence-space">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Identify <m>P \in \CAb</m> with <m>\ker(\ZZ[\underline{\NN_\infty}] \to \ZZ[\underline{\infty}])</m>
          and the underlying set of <m>P</m> with <m>\ker(\ZZ[\NN_\infty] \to \ZZ[\infty]) \cong \ZZ[\NN]</m>.
          Then for <m>S \in \Prof</m>, <m>P(S) = \Cts(S, \ker(\ZZ[\NN_\infty] \to \ZZ[\infty]))</m> 
          consists of functions <m>f \colon S \to \ZZ[\NN]</m> with the following properties.
          <ol>
            <li>
              The image of <m>f</m> belongs to the subset <m>\{\sum_n a_n[n] \in \ZZ[\NN]\colon \sum_n |a_n| \leq c\}</m> for some <m>c \in \NN</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Every level set of <m>f</m> (i.e., the preimage of a point) is a closed subset of <m>S</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              For any <m>n_0 \in \NN</m>, <m>f</m> assumes only finitely many values not contained in <m>\ZZ[n_0 + \NN]</m>.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Left to the reader.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
   <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\ZZ[\hat{x}]</m> be another copy of <m>P</m> viewed as an algebra over <m>\ZZ[x]</m> via <m>x^n \mapsto [n]</m>.
          Then
          <me>
            \Hom_{\CAb}(\ZZ[\hat{x}], \ZZ[\hat{q}]) = \bigcup_{n \gt 0} \varprojlim_m \left( \ZZ[q]/(q^m)_{\leq n} [x] \right)
          </me>
          where the subscript <m>\leq n</m> means consider sums <m>\sum_j a_j q^j</m> with <m>\sum_j |a_j| \leq n</m>
          (that is, we take the subring of <m>\ZZ[q]/(q^m)[x]</m> in which the coefficient of each power of <m>x</m> satisfies this condition).
          Similarly, for <m>S = \varprojlim_i S_i \in \Prof</m>,
          <me>
            \Hom_{\CAb}(P, P[\underline{S}]) = \bigcup_{n \gt 0} \varprojlim_{m, i} \left( \ZZ[q]/(q^m)[S_i]_{\leq n} [x] \right)
          </me>
          where the subscript <m>\leq n</m> means consider sums <m>\sum_{j,s} a_j q^j[s]</m> with <m>\sum_{j,s} |a_{j,s}| \leq n</m>
          (for the coefficient of each power of <m>x</m>).
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Left to the reader.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
 
     <remark>
      <p>
        As a corollary of the proof of <xref ref="prop-solid-vs-presumptively-solid"/>, we note that the operation <m>\otimes</m> on <m>\CAb</m>
        preserves <m>\CAb_{\solid}</m>, so the solid tensor product on solid objects just reduces to the ordinary tensor product. Namely,
        it suffices to check that <m>\ZZ[\underline{S}}_\solid \otimes \ZZ[\underline{T}]_\solid \to \ZZ[\underline{S \otimes T}]_\solid</m> 
        is an isomorphism whenever
        <m>S, T \in \Prof</m>. For this, we may assume that <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> are both infinite,
        then note that the construction of the isomorphisms <m>\ZZ[\underline{S}]_\solid \cong \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m>,
        <m>\ZZ[\underline{T}]_\solid \cong \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> in <xref ref="lem-identify-solidification-of-free"/> also yields
        an isomorphism <m>\ZZ[\underline{S \times T}]_\solid \cong \prod_{\NN \times \NN} \underline{\ZZ}</m> in such a way that the map 
        <m>\ZZ[\underline{S}}_\solid \otimes \ZZ[\underline{T}]_\solid \to \ZZ[\underline{S \otimes T}]_\solid</m> corresponds to the canonical identification
        <me>
          \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ} \otimes \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ} \cong \prod_{\NN \times \NN} 
        </me>
      </p>
    </remark>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-separate-sum-by-order-of-k">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>(s_n)_{n \in \NN}</m> be a sequence of integers such that <m>|s_n| = O(n^k)</m> for some positive integer <m>k</m>.
          (Here the big-O notation means that there exists <m>c \gt 0</m> such that <m>|s_n| \leq c(n+1)^k</m> for all <m>n</m>.)
          Then there exist integers <m>t_{i,j}</m> for <m>i,j \geq 0</m> and a constant <m>c' \gt 0</m> such that:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <m>|t_{i,j}| \leq c'(j+1)^{k-1}</m> for all <m>i,j</m>;
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>s_n = \sum_{i=0}^n t_{i,n-i}</m> for all <m>n</m>.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          The formula
          <me>
            t_{i,j} := \left \lfloor \frac{s_{i+j} + j}{i+j+1} \right\rfloor
          </me>
          has the desired effect.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-map-to-universal-liquefaction">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The map <m>A_0^{\triangleright} \to A^{\triangleright}</m> induces a surjection <m>(A_0^{\triangleright})_{\liquid q} \to A^{\triangleright}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Per <xref ref="eq-universal-liquefaction"/>, it suffices to check that for <m>k \gt 0</m> and <m>c \gt 0</m>, an arbitrary series 
          <m>s = \sum_{m \in \NN} s_{m} q^m</m> with <m>|s_{m}| \leq c(m+1)^k</m> for all <m>m</m> belongs to the image of <m>(A_0^{\triangleright})_{\liquid q}</m>.
          We proceed by induction on <m>k</m>. In the base case <m>k=0</m>,
          <me>
            s = \sum_{m=0}^\infty (s_{2m} q^m + s_{2m+1}q^{m+1}) q^m
          </me>
          and the coefficients of <m>q^m</m> form a null sequence in <m>A_0^{\triangleright}</m>.
          For the induction step, define <m>t_{i,j}</m> according to <xref ref="lem-separate-sum-by-order-of-k"/> and
          set <m>t_i := \sum_{j=0}^\infty t_{i,j} q^j</m>, so that
          <me>
            s = \sum_{i=0}^\infty t_i q^i
          </me>;
          then each <m>t_i</m> belongs to <m>(A_0^{\triangleright})_{\liquid q}</m> by the induction hypothesis,
          but the <m>t_i</m> do not form a null sequence.
          However, as in the base case we may rewrite this sum as
          <me>
            s = \sum_{i=0}^\infty (t_{2i} q^i + t_{2m+1}q^{i+1}) q^i
          </me>
          and now the coefficients of <m>q^i</m> do form a null sequence in <m>(A_0^{\triangleright})_{\liquid q}</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>

    <remark>
      <p>
        By writing <m>\Ext^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(A_{\solid},\ZZ_{\solid})</m> as <m>\Hom_{\ZZ_\solid}(\ZZ_\solid, \iExt^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(A_\solid, \ZZ_\solid))</m>
        and then invoking <xref ref="rem-solid-to-ordinary-is-faithful"/>, we may see that 
        <m>\Ext^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(A_{\solid},\ZZ_{\solid}) = 0</m> if and only if <m>\iExt^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(A_\solid, \ZZ_\solid) = 0</m>.
        That is, we may state <xref ref="prop-Whitehead-for-solid"/> in terms of the vanishing of the external Ext instead of the internal one.
      </p>
    </remark>
   <p>
      In practice, we will typically think of solid abelian groups in a third manner, following <xref ref="rem-compare-solid-to-top-ab-group"/>.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-solid-topological-groups">
      <p>
        It follows from <xref ref="prop-solid-vs-presumptively-solid"/> that the functor <m>\Ab_\solid \to \CAb_\solid</m> factors through the category <m>\TopAb^{\seq}</m>
        of sequential topological abelian groups: 
        this is evident for the generator <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ_\solid</m> (which corresponds to <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ</m> for the discrete topology on <m>\NN</m>)
        and then follows formally by taking colimits. Let <m>\TopAb_\solid</m> denote the resulting full subcategory of <m>\TopAb</m>;
        it is equivalent to both <m>\Ab_\solid</m> and <m>\CAb_\solid</m>; however, the tensor product <m>\otimes_\solid</m> on <m>\TopAb_\solid</m> 
        is not inherited from a tensor product on <m>\TopAb</m>.
      </p>
    </definition>
     <example>
      <p>
        If <m>R</m> carries a submultiplicative seminorm <m>|\bullet|</m>, then we may define the <term>Gauss seminorm</term> on <m>R[T]</m> relative to the norm on <m>R</m>
        taking <m>\sum_i a_i T^i</m> to <m>\max_i \{|a_i|\}</m>. This is again submultiplicative; if <m>|\bullet|</m> is multiplicative, then the Gauss seminorm is also multiplicative
        (this amounts to a version of Gauss's lemma on factorization of integer polynomials, hence the terminology).
      </p>
      <p>
        More generally, for <m>\rho \geq 0</m>, we define the <term><m>\rho</m>-Gauss seminorm</term> on <m>R[T]</m> relative to the seminorm on <m>R</m>
        to take <m>\sum_i a_i T^i</m> to <m>\max_i \{|a_i| \rho^i\}</m>. This is again submultiplicative, and even multiplicative if the original seminorm is multiplicative.
      </p>
      <p>
        More evidently, if <m>\rho \gt 0</m> and we start with a norm on <m>R</m>, then the <m>\rho</m>-Gauss seminorm on <m>R[T]</m> is a norm, so we also refer to it as the
        <term><m>\rho</m>-Gauss norm</term> on <m>R[T]</m> (or the <term>Gauss norm</term> if <m>\rho = 1</m>).
      </p>
    </example>
    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a ring equipped with a multiplicative seminorm <m>|\bullet|</m>. Then for any <m>\rho \geq 0</m>, the <m>\rho</m>-Gauss seminorm <m>|\bullet|_\rho</m> on <m>R[T]</m>
          relative to <m>|\bullet|</m> is again multiplicative.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Our goal is to verify that <m>|xy|_\rho = |x|_\rho|y|_\rho</m> for all <m>x,y \in R[T]</m>; there is nothing to check unless <m>|x|_\rho, |y|_\rho \gt 0</m>.
          In that case, if we write <m>x = \sum_i x_i T^i</m>, <m>y = \sum_j x_j T^j</m>, then there is a maximal index <m>i_0</m> for which <m>|x_{i_0}| \rho^{i_0} = |x|_\rho</m>
          and a maximal index <m>j_0</m> for which <m>|y_{j_0}| \rho^{j_0} = |y|_\rho</m>. 
          Now set <m>k := i_0 + j_0</m> and write the coefficient of <m>T^{i_0+j_0}</m> in <m>xy</m> as the sum of <m>x_i y_j</m> over all pairs of nonnegative integers <m>i,j</m>
          with <m>i+j=k</m>.
          <ul>
            <li>
              If <m>j \gt j_0</m>, then <m>|x_i| \rho^i \leq |x|_\rho</m>, <m>|y_j| \rho^j \lt |y|_\rho</m>
              and so <m>|x_i y_j| \rho^k \lt |x|_\rho |y|_\rho</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              If <m>i \gt i_0</m>, then <m>|x_i| \rho^i \lt |x|_\rho</m>, <m>|y_j| \rho^j \leq |y|_\rho</m>
              and so <m>|x_i y_j| \rho^k \lt |x|_\rho |y|_\rho</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              This leaves only the case <m>i=i_0, j = j_0</m>, in which case <m>|x_i| \rho^i = |x|_\rho</m>, <m>|y_j| \rho^j = |y|_\rho</m>
              and so <m>|x_i y_j| \rho^k = |x|_\rho |y|_\rho</m>.
            </li>
          </ul>
          as <m>x_{i_0} y_{j_0}</m> plus
          a complementary term <m>z</m> and we have
          <me>
            |x_{i_0} y_{j_0}| \rho^{i_0+j_0} = |x|_\rho |y|_\rho.
          </me>
          Meanwhile, <m>z</m>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
     <remark>
      <p>
        If <m>A</m> is not sheafy, then <xref ref="lem-sheafy-exact-sequence"/> remains valid as a statement in the derived category of <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>
        if we give all of the terms their natural derived structure per <xref ref="rem-rational-subspace-derived"/>,
        which is to say we view the other rings in the sequence as animated condensed rings.
        The same holds if we allow <m>A</m> itself to be an animated condensed ring.
      </p>
    </remark>    <definition>
      <p>
        For <m>A</m> a complete Huber pair, the <term>structure presheaf</term> on <m>\Spa A</m> is defined on rational subspaces by
        <me>
          U(\tfrac{f_1,\dots,f_n}{g}) \mapsto A^{\triangleright}\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle.
        </me>
        When this presheaf is a sheaf, we may view <m>\Spa A</m> as a locally ringed space,
        and then define a <term>adic space</term> to be a locally ringed space covered by open subspaces of this form.
      </p>
      <p>
        One serious complication in Huber's theory is that the structure presheaf is not always a sheaf;
        when this occurs we say that <m>A</m> is <term>sheafy</term>.
        (This turns out to depend only on <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>.)
        The question of when a Huber pair is sheafy is quite subtle;
        see <xref ref="bib-Hansen-Kedlaya"/> for a thorough discussion.
      </p>
    </definition>

       <p>
        
        A corresponding issue in the context of solid analytic rings is that the quotient by the ideal <m>(f_1- gT_1, \dots, f_n - gT_n)</m> may not equal the
        <em>derived</em> quotient. The latter is represented by the Koszul complex associated to the sequence <m>f_1  - gT_1, \dots, f_n - gT_n</m>; when <m>n=1</m>
        this is just the two-term complex
        <me>
          A^{\triangleright}[T_1] \stackrel{\times f_1 - g T_1}{\to} A^{\triangleright}[T_1]
        </me>
        with the second term in degree 0.
      </p>
      <p>
        To keep the exposition simple, we will focus on <em>sheafy</em> solid analytic rings, for which these issues do not occur
        (<xref ref="def-sheafy-analytic"/>). In the solid setting one can finesse the issue by replacing animated rings with <term>animated</term> analytic rings,
        for which quotienting by the ideal <m>(f_1- gT_1, \dots, f_n - gT_n)</m> preserves the derived structure.
      </p>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-exact-sequence-sheafy-persistence">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The sequences <xref ref="eq-represent-localization-as-quotient"/>, <xref ref="eq-represent-localization-as-quotient2"/>,
          and <xref ref="eq-sheafy-exact-sequence"/> are exact whenever <m>f,g \in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m> generate the unit ideal.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Using <xref ref="thm-solid-sheafy"/>, we may reduce the claim to the situation where either <m>f/g</m> or <m>g/f</m> is a power-bounded element of <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>.
          In those cases we can deduce the claims directly from <xref ref="lem-sheafy-exact-sequence"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A morphism <m>A \to B</m> of analytic rings can be specified by giving:
          <ul>
            <li>
              a morphism <m>A^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}</m> of condensed rings with <m>B^{\triangleright} \in \Mod_A</m>;
            </li>
            <li>
              for each <m>S \in \Prof</m>, a morphism <m>A[\underline{S}] \to B[\underline{S}]</m> functorial in <m>S</m>;
            </li>
          </ul>
          such that for each morphism <m>\underline{S} \to A^{\triangleright}</m> in <m>\CAb</m>, we have a commuting diagram
          <figure>
            <image>
              <latex-image>
                \xymatrix{
                  A[\underline{S}] \ar[r] \ar[d] &amp; A^{\triangleright} \ar[d] \\
                  B[\underline{S}] \ar[r] &amp; B^{\triangleright}
                }
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
          where the rows are induced by <m>\underline{S} \to A^{\triangleright}</m>
          and <m>\underline{S} \to A^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}</m> by adjunction.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We must check that for every <m>M \in \Mod_B</m>, its restriction of scalars along <m>A^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}</m>
          belongs to <m>A</m>; it suffices to check this for <m>B[\underline{S}]</m> with <m>S \in \Prof</m> as every object in <m>\Mod_S</m>
          is a colimit of these.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rest of the proof to follow.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <definition>
      <p>
        For <m>A \in \AnRing</m> and <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g \in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m>, define the <term>rational localization</term>
        <m>A \to A \left \langle \frac{f_1,\dots,f_n}{g} \right\rangle</m> by analogy with <xref ref="prop-solid-rational-localization"/>:
        form <m>A[T_1,\dots,T_n]/(f_1 - g T_1,\dots,f_n - g T_n)</m> and then liquefy with respect to <m>T_1,\dots,T_n</m>.
        When <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g</m> generate the unit ideal, this construction is again intrinsically underived
        (as in <xref ref="rem-localization-is-underived"/>).
      </p>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Staying in the solid setting for the moment, let us consider a variant of the previous construction.
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-Beauville-Laszlo-exact-seq">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a solid analytic ring. Then the sequences
          <md>
            <mrow>
              0 \to A[T] \to A\langle T \rangle \oplus A((T^{-1})) \to A \langle T \rangle\llbracket T^{-1} \rrbracket \rangle \to 0
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              0 \to A[T^{-1}] \to A\langle T \rangle[T^{-1}] \oplus A\llbracket T^{-1}\rrbracket \to A \langle T \rangle\llbracket T^{-1} \rrbracket \rangle \to 0
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              0 to A[T^{\pm}] \to A\langle T \rangle[T^{-1}] \oplus A((T^{-1})) \to A \langle T \rangle\llbracket T^{-1} \rrbracket \rangle \to 0
            </mrow>
          </md>
          are exact.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Start with the split exact sequence
          <me>
            0 \to A \to A \langle T \rangle \oplus A((T^{-1})) \to A\langle T \rangle \llbracket T^{-1} \rrbracket \to 0.
          </me>
          and take solid tensor products with <m>A[T], A[T^{-1}], A[T^{\pm}]</m> over <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Any composition of weak rational localizations is again a weak rational localization.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          The first point is that if <m>A \to B \to C</m> is a sequence of rational localizations, 
          then the second localization <m>B \to C</m> can always be described using parameters
          in <m>A^{\triangleright}</m> rather than <m>B^{\triangleright}</m>. Namely, there is no change if we perturb the <m>f_i/g</m> by an element of <m>B^{\circ \circ}</m>,
          so we can at least put the parameters in <m>A^{\triangleright}\left[\tfrac{1}{g} \right]</m>. We can now clear denominators by multiplying through by a suitable power of <m>g</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Now the first localization is defined by some parameters <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g \in A^{\triangleright}</m>, 
          and the second is defined by some parameters <m>f'_1,\dots,f'_m,g' \in A^{\triangleright}</m>. The composition is then defined by the parameters
          <me>
            f_1g', \dots, f_ng', f'_1g, \dots,f'_m g, gg'
          </me>.
        </p>
      </proof>
          the following sequences are exact:
          <mdn>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-represent-localization-as-quotient">
              0 \to A^{\triangleright}[T]_{\liquid T} \stackrel{\times f-gT}{\to} A^{\triangleright}[T]_{\liquid T} \to  A\left\langle \tfrac{f}{g} \right\rangle^{\triangleright} \to 0
            </mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eq-represent-localization-as-quotient2">
              0 \to A^{\triangleright}[T^{\pm}]_{\liquid T^{\pm}} \stackrel{\times f-gT}{\to} A^{\triangleright}[T^{\pm}]_{\liquid T^{\pm}} \to  A\left\langle \tfrac{f}{g},\tfrac{g}{f} \right\rangle^{\triangleright} \to 0
            </mrow>
    <definition>
      <p>
        For <m>A</m> an analytic ring, a morphism <m>f\colon P \to Q</m> between compact objects in <m>\calD(\Mod_A)</m> is <term>trace class</term> if
        there exists a morphism <m>g \colon A \to P^\vee \otimes^L_A Q</m> for which <m>f</m> equals the composition
        <me>
          P \stackrel{1 \otimes g}{\to} P \otimes^L_A P^\vee \otimes^L_A Q \to Q
        </me>
        in which the second map is induced by the contraction <m>P \otimes^L_A P^\vee \to A</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        An object of <m>\calD(\Mod_A)</m> is <term>basic nuclear</term> if it can be written as a colimit
        <me>
          P_0 \to P_1 \to \cdots
        </me>
        of trace class morphisms between compact objects. Any such object is nuclear, and conversely every nuclear object is a filtered colimit of basic
        nuclear objects (<xref ref="bib-Clausen-Scholze-analytic"/>, Proposition 13.13).
      </p>
    </definition>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="thm-pseudocoherent-descent"/>, the complex <m>M_1 \oplus M_2 \to M_{12}</m> of <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-modules is pseudocoherent;
          it is visibly concentrated in degrees <m>[0,1]</m>. Using <xref ref="lem-covering-by-local"/>, we may further deduce that the cohomology in degree <m>0</m> vanishes,
          so we get a complex associated to an <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module <m>M</m> placed in degree <m>0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>A</m> is sheafy, by <xref ref="prop-sheafy-by-localizations-are-Huber"/> taking a rational localization of <m>A</m> commutes with passage to the associated
          solid analytic ring <m>\underline{A}</m>. Using <xref ref="thm-sheaf-qcoh-for-adic"/>,
          we can interpret a vector bundle on <m>\Spa A</m> as giving rise to a complex in <m>\calD(\Mod_{\underline{A}})</m>
          which locally can be represented by a finite projective module placed in degree <m>0</m>.
          We need to show that this implies that the original complex can also be so represented.
        </p>
        <p>
          Our original complex, when truncated up to degree <m>-1</m> or down to degree <m>1</m>,
          becomes a complex that base extends to zero, and so by <xref ref="thm-sheaf-qcoh-for-adic"/> is isomorphic to the zero complex.
          We may thus reduce to the case where we start with a single module <m>\underline{M} \in \Mod_{\underline{A}}</m> placed in degree <m>0</m> whose base extensions are 
          represented by finite projective modules placed in degree <m>0</m>, and we wish to deduce that
          <m>\underline{M}</m> is itself represented by a finite projective <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module. 
          Beware that we do not yet know that <m>\underline{M}</m> is represented by an <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module <m>M</m>; we will only infer this in the next step.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since we know that <m>\underline{M} \otimes_{\underline{A}}^L \underline{A_i}^{\triangleright}</m> is concentrated in degree <m>0</m>, we have an exact sequence
          <men xml:id="eq-M-exact-sequence">
            0 \to \underline{M} \to \underline{M} \otimes_{\underline{A}} \underline{A_1}^{\triangleright} \oplus \underline{M} \otimes_{\underline{A}} \underline{A_2}^{\triangleright} \to M \otimes_{\underline{A}} \underline{A_{12}}^{\triangleright} \to 0
          </men>
          in which every term other than <m>\underline{M}</m> is represented by a topological <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module 
          (namely a finite projective module over some <m>A_i^{\triangleright}</m>).
          The same then follows for <m>\underline{M}</m> because kernels of topological groups are preserved by the passage to condensed groups;
          that is, we now can interpret <m>\underline{M}</m> as being represented by a topological <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module <m>M</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We next verify that we can choose a morphism <m>F \to M</m> from a finite free <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module <m>F</m>
          which induces a surjection 
          <m>\underline{F} \otimes_{\underline{A}} \underline{A_i}^{\triangleright} \to \underline{M} \otimes_{\underline{A}} \underline{A_i}^{\triangleright}</m> 
          for <m>i=1,2</m>;
          this would be automatic if the tensor products in <xref ref="eq-M-exact-sequence"/> were purely algebraic, but as it stands some argument is needed.
          Since we are now talking about Huber rings rather than condensed rings, we can at least say that the algebraic tensor product 
          <m>M \otimes_{A^{\triangleright}} A_i^{\triangleright}</m>
          has dense image in the underlying topological module of <m>\underline{M} \otimes_{\underline{A}} \underline{A}_i^{\triangleright}</m>.
          We may thus deduce the existence of the desired morphism from <xref ref="lem-approximate-basis"/>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If we now view <m>\underline{F} \to \underline{M}</m> as a two-term complex in <m>\calD(\Mod_{\underline{A}})</m> with <m>\underline{M}</m> placed in degree <m>0</m>,
          its base extension to <m>\calD(\Mod_{\underline{A_i}})</m> has vanishing cohomology in degree <m>0</m>.
          By <xref ref="thm-sheaf-qcoh-for-adic"/> again, <m>\underline{F} \to \underline{M}</m> itself has vanishing cohomology in degree <m>0</m>, 
          meaning that <m>\underline{F} \to \underline{M}</m> is surjective in <m>\Mod_{\underline{A}}</m>.
          This in turn implies that <m>F \to M</m> is surjective, so <m>M</m> is a finitely generated <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module.
        </p>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="thm-sheaf-qcoh-for-adic"/> again, for any <m>N \in \Mod_{\underline{A}}</m>, <m>\iExt^1_{\underline{A}}(\underline{M}, N) = 0</m>;
          consequently, <m>\underline{M}</m> is projective in <m>\Mod_{\underline{A}}</m>.
          While this does not itself imply that <m>M</m> is projective as an <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module,
          we do have a surjection <m>\underline{F} \to \underline{M}</m> in <m>\Mod_{\underline{A}}</m> which we can now split;
          this implies that <m>F \to M</m> is split, and hence that <m>M</m> is a projective <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module.
        </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-approximate-basis">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a complete Huber ring. Let <m>M</m> be a finite projective <m>A</m>-module, topologized as a quotient of some finite free <m>A</m>-module
          (note that this topology is independent of the choice). Let <m>S</m> be a subset of <m>M</m> whose accumulation points include a set of <m>A</m>-module generators of <m>M</m>.
          Then <m>S</m> generates <m>M</m> as an <m>A</m>-module; in particular, it contains a finite subset which generates <m>M</m> as an <m>A</m>-module.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Since <m>M</m> is a finite projective <m>A</m>-module, we can write it as a summand of a finite free module <m>F \cong M \oplus M'</m>.
          By adding to <m>S</m> a finite set of <m>A</m>-module generators of <m>M'</m>, we may reduce to the case <m>M = F</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We thus assume hereafter that <m>M</m> is free on the basis <m>e_1,\dots,e_n</m>. By hypothesis, we can choose elements <m>e'_1,\dots,e'_n \in S</m>
          such that the <m>n \times n</m> matrix <m>B</m> with <m>e'_j = \sum_i B_{ij} e_i</m> has the property that <m>1-B</m> has entries in <m>A^{\circ \circ}</m>.
          Consequently, <m>1-\det(B) \in A^{\circ \circ}</m> and so <m>B</m> is invertible; this proves the claim.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-pseudocoherent-complexes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For <m>A</m> a sheafy Huber pair, the category of pseudocoherent complexes of <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-modules admits descent for the adic topology.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          As in the proof of <xref ref="cor-vector-bundles"/>, we translate this into the statement that if we start with a complex <m>\underline{M}</m> in <m>\calD(\Mod_{\underline{A}})</m>
          whose base extensions to <m>\calD(\Mod_{\underline{A}_i})</m> are represented by bounded-above complexes of finite projective <m>A_i^{\triangleright}</m>-modules,
          then <m>\underline{M}</m> is represented by a bounded-above complex of finite projective <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-modules.
          This condition means that some lower truncation of the original complex base extends to zero,
          and so by <xref ref="thm-sheaf-qcoh-for-adic"/> is isomorphic to zero; we may thus reduce to the case where our original complex is itself bounded above.
        </p>
        <p>
          Suppose the largest degree that occurs is <m>n</m>.
          By arguing as in the proof of <xref ref="cor-vector-bundles"/>, we obtain a finite free <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module <m>F</m>
          and a morphism <m>\underline{F}[n] \to \underline{M}</m> which induces a surjection of cohomology in degree <m>n</m>.
          By forming a mapping cone, we obtain a representation of <m>\underline{M}</m> by a complex with <m>\underline{F}</m> placed in degree <m>n</m>
          and zero terms in higher degrees. By applying the same argument to the mapping cone and iterating,
          we build a representation of <m>\underline{M}</m> with terms represented by finite projective <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-modules placed in all degrees <m>\leq n</m>
          and zero terms in higher degrees.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>
        <p>
          We first upgrade 
          <xref ref="lem-descent-standard-covering"/> to an <m>\infty</m>-categorical analogue by exhibiting an equivalence
          <men xml:id="eq-glueing-equivalence-qcoh">
            \calD(\Mod_A) \to \calD(\Mod_{A \left\langle f/g \right\rangle}) \times_{\calD(\Mod_{A \left\langle f/g, g/f \right\rangle})} \calD(\Mod_{A \left\langle g/f \right\rangle})
          </men>.
          Namely, in the proof of <xref ref="lem-descent-standard-covering"/> we <q>explicitly</q> checked that the unit and counit are isomorphisms,
          in that our description yields explicit (and functorial) inverse morphisms and chain homotopy equivalences of the compositions with the identity morphisms.
          We can thus formally deduce the conclusion from <xref ref="prop-standard-binary-coverings-Huber"/>.
        </p>
      <p>
        For any morphism <m>A \to C</m>, <m>B^{\triangleright} \otimes_A^L C^{\triangleright}</m>
        is the derived derived <m>f</m>-completion of <m>C^{\triangleright}</m>. It thus suffices to check that this completion is equal to the naive derived <m>f</m>-completion.
        For this, as suggested in <xref ref="rem-sum-null-against-f"/>,
        we may proceed in two steps. We first force <m>f</m> to become topologically nilpotent by passing from <m>C</m> to <m>(\ZZ[\hat{q}] \otimes C)/(q-f)</m>;
        this quotient equals the derived quotient because <m>q-f</m> is not a zero divisor in <m>\ZZ[\hat{q}] \otimes C^{\triangleright}</m>.
        (The sections over <m>S \in \Prof</m> are obtained by sheafifying <m>P(S) \otimes C^{\triangleright}(S) \subseteq \prod_{s \in S} C^{\triangleright}(*)[q]</m>,
        where it is visible that multiplication by the monic polynomial <m>q-f</m> is injective.)
        We then liquefy with respect to <m>f</m>, which as usual is an underived operation on rings (<xref ref="rem-liquefaction-kills-ext1"/>).
      </p>
    <p>
      We compare the previous discussion with the following definition in algebraic geometry.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-absolutely-flat-rings">
      <p>
        A morphism <m>A \to B</m> in <m>\Ring</m> is <term>absolutely flat</term> (or <term>weakly étale</term>) if <m>A \to B</m>
        and <m>B \otimes_A B \to B</m> are both flat. In particular, <m>B \otimes_A^L B \to B</m> is flat.
      </p>
      <p>
        For instance, any étale morphism is absolutely flat.
        Also, any colimit of absolutely flat morphisms is absolutely flat;
        in particular, localization at any multiplicative subset (which need not be of finite type) is absolutely flat.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>pro-étale topology</term> on <m>\Ring^{\op}</m>, as considered by Bhatt<ndash/>Scholze <xref ref="bib-Bhatt-Scholze-proetale"/>,
        is the topology generated by finite disjoint unions and morphisms which are both faithfully flat and absolutely flat.
        This includes more coverings than the Zariski topology and the étale topology, but fewer than the fpqc topology.
      </p>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Modeling <xref ref="def-absolutely-flat-rings"/> in analytic rings is a bit subtle; we propose the following.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <p>
        A morphism <m>A \to B</m> of analytic rings is <term>absolutely flat</term>
        if <m>B \otimes^L_B</m> is underived and <m>B</m> is projective as an object of <m>\Mod_{B \otimes_A B}</m>.
        Any idempotent morphism is absolutely flat.
      </p>
      <p>
        The corresponding <term>pro-étale topology</term> on <m>\AnRing^{\op}</m> is again generated by finite families of absolutely flat morphisms <m>\{\AnSpec A_i \to \AnSpec A\}_{i \in I}</m>
        such that for <m>B := \bigoplus_i A_i</m>, the complex <xref ref="eq-proetale-topology"/> is exact
        (once again assuming all the tensor products in question are underived).
        Note that this is no longer equivalent to <xref ref="eq-idempotent-topology"/> being exact.
      </p>
    </definition>
  <subsection>
    <title>Derivedness revisited</title>
    <p>
      Let us unpack <xref ref="exa-rational-localization-is-idempotent"/> a bit to further clarify why rational localizations of solid analytic rings
      are sometimes derived, and more to the point why they are sometimes consistently <em>not</em> derived.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <p>
        A condensed abelian group <m>M</m> is <term>separated</term> if the coordinate map <m>\bigoplus_\NN M \to \prod_\NN M</m> is injective. 
      </p>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We may infer from <xref ref="eq-Zariski-localization-idempotent"/> that the object <m>M</m> used in 
      <xref ref="exa-Koszul-complex-not-acyclic"/> is not separated. Here is the universal version of that example.
    </p>
    <example>
      <p>
        Let <m>M</m> be the condensed abelian group corresponding to the solid abelian group <m>M_\solid</m> described in
        <xref ref="eq-solid-object-with-zero-underlying"/> with <m>R = \ZZ, I = \NN</m>; that is,
        <me>
          M_\solid = \coker\left( \left( \prod_\NN \ZZ \right)_\solid \to \prod_\NN \ZZ_\solid
        </me>
        and in particular
        <m>
          M_\solid\left( \prod_I \ZZ_\solid \right) = \left( \prod_\NN \bigoplus_I \ZZ \right) / \left( \bigoplus_I \prod_\NN \ZZ \right)
        </m>.
        (see <xref ref="eq-solid-object-with-zero-underlying"/>) is not separated.
        We have
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \left(\bigoplus_\NN M \right)\left(\prod_I \ZZ_\solid \right) = \left( 
          </mrow>
        </md>
        <m>M := \coker(\ZZ[T] \to \ZZ\llbracket T \rrbracket)</m>
        <m>M = \coker(\underline{\ZZ}[T] \to \prod_n \underline{\ZZ}[T]/(T^n))</m> is not separated.
        We may check this in <m>\Ab_\solid</m>:
        start with the exact sequence
        <men xml:id="eq-present-M-not-separated">
          0 \to \ZZ[T] \to \ZZ\llbracket T \rrbracket \to M \to 0
        </men>
        whose evaluation on <m>\prod_I \ZZ_\solid</m> is 
        <me>
          0 \to \left( \prod_I \ZZ \right)[T] \to \prod_I \ZZ\llbracket T \rrbracket \to M\left(\prod_I \ZZ_\solid \right) \to 0
        </me>.
        Taking coproducts over <m>\NN</m> in <xref ref="eq-present-M-not-separated"/> yields an exact sequence...
        Taking products over <m>\NN</m> in <xref ref="eq-present-M-not-separated"/> yields an exact sequence...
        
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \left(\bigoplus_\NN M \right)\left( \prod_I \ZZ_\solid \right) &amp;= \bigoplus_\NN \bigoplus_I \ZZ \llbracket T \rrbracket/\ZZ[T]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \left(\prod_\NN M \right)\left( \prod_I \ZZ_\solid \right) &amp;= \prod_\NN \bigoplus_I \ZZ \llbracket T \rrbracket/\ZZ[T]
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>
      <p>
        For example, if <m>M = \coker(\underline{\ZZ}[T] \to \prod_n \underline{\ZZ}[T]/(T^n))</m>, then <m>M</m> is not condensed:
        in <m>\Ab_\solid</m> we have
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \left(\bigoplus_\NN M \right)\left( \prod_I \ZZ_\solid \right) &amp;= \bigoplus_\NN \bigoplus_I \ZZ \llbracket T \rrbracket/\ZZ[T]
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \left(\prod_\NN M \right)\left( \prod_I \ZZ_\solid \right) &amp;= \prod_\NN \bigoplus_I \ZZ \llbracket T \rrbracket/\ZZ[T]
          </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Taking this further, in <m>\Mod_A</m> we can reinterpret the map <m>A[T] \to A \llbracket T \rrbracket</m> as the map
        <m>\bigoplus_\NN A \to \prod_\NN A</m>, which is of course the base extension of the map <m>\bigoplus_\NN \underline{\ZZ} \to \prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m>.
        The injectivity of <m>A[T] \to A \llbracket T \rrbracket</m> is then equivalent to the equality
        <me>
          A \otimes_{\ZZ} \ZZ \llbracket T \rrbracket/\ZZ[T] \cong A \otimes^L_{\ZZ} \ZZ \llbracket T \rrbracket/\ZZ[T]
        </me>.
        Using <xref ref="ref-liquefaction-is-underived"/>, we can further equate with the equality
        <me>
          A \otimes_{\ZZ} \ZZ \llbracket T \rrbracket/\ZZ[T]_{\liquid T} \cong A \otimes^L_{\ZZ} \ZZ \llbracket T \rrbracket/\ZZ[T]_{\liquid T}
        </me>.
      </p>
  </subsection>
      <p>
        By construction, for <m>|I| \leq \kappa</m>,
        <men xml:id="eq-base-extension-on-product">
          \left(\prod_I R_\solid \right) \otimes_{R_{\solid}} S_{\solid} = \prod_I S_\solid.
        </men>
        More generally, for any <m>M_i \in \Mod_{R_\solid}</m>, by writing <m>M_i</m> as a colimit over 
        objects of the form <m>\prod_J R_{\solid}</m> and using <xref ref="eq-base-extension-on-product"/>,
        <men>
          \left(\prod_I M_i \right) \otimes_{R_{\solid}} S_{\solid} = \prod_I (M_i \otimes_{R_\solid} S_\solid).
        </men>
      </p>
        <me>
          \prod_{n=1}^\infty \ZZ[1/p]_{\solid} \to \prod_{n=1}^\infty \ZZ[1/p]_{\solid} \to M \otimes_{\ZZ_{\solid}} \ZZ[1/p]_{\solid} \to 0
        </me>
        is again exact. However, the map on <m>\prod_{n=1}^\infty \ZZ[1/p]_{\solid}</m> is now invertible,
        so <m>M \otimes_{\ZZ_{\solid}} \ZZ[1/p]_{\solid} = 0</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Putting the two facts together, we see that <m>\ZZ_{\solid} \to M</m> is a monomorphism, but its base extension
        <m>\ZZ[1/p]_{\solid} \to M \otimes_{\ZZ_{\solid}} \ZZ[1/p]_{\solid}</m> has zero target and so is definitely not a monomorphism!
        That is, the base extension functor is not exact, which is to say that <m>\ZZ[1/p]_{\solid}</m> is not a flat <m>\ZZ_{\solid}</m>-module.
        (The same logic applies to <m>R \to R[1/f]</m> whenever <m>f \in R</m> is not a zero divisor.)
    <proposition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For <m>R \to S</m> a ring homomorphism, the restriction of scalars functor <m>F\colon \Mod_{S_\solid} \to \Mod_{R_{\solid}}</m> is exact.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Start with an exact sequence in <m>\Mod_{S_{\solid}}</m>:
          <me>
            0 \to M_1 \to M_2 \to M_3 \to 0.
          </me>
          Evaluate on <m>\prod_I S_{\solid}</m> to obtain another exact sequence:
          <me>
            0 \to \Hom_{S_\solid}(\prod_I S_{\solid}, M_1) \to \Hom_{S_\solid}(\prod_I S_{\solid}, M_2) \to 
            \Hom_{S_\solid}(\prod_I S_{\solid}, M_3) \to 0.
          </me>
          Apply adjunction between restriction of scalars and extension of scalars to obtain another exact sequence
          <me>
            0 \to \Hom_{R_\solid}(\prod_I R_{\solid}, F(M_1)) \to \Hom_{R_\solid}(\prod_I R_{\solid}, F(M_2)) \to 
            \Hom_{R_\solid}(\prod_I R_{\solid}, F(M_3)) \to 0.
          </me>
          Finally, infer from this that the sequence
          <me>
            0 \to F(M_1) \to F(M_2) \to F(M_3) \to 0
          </me>
          is exact, proving the claim.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
      <p>
        More generally, for any <m>M_i, N_j \in \Mod_{R_\solid}</m>,
        <men xml:id="eq-solid-product-on-one-free">
          \left(\prod_{i \in I} M_i\right) \otimes_{R_\solid} \left(\prod_{j \in I} M_j\right) = \prod_{i \in I, j \in J} (M_i \otimes_{R_\solid} N_j);
        </men>
        namely, this holds for <m>M_i = N_j = R_\solid</m> by <xref ref="eq-solid-product-on-one-free"/> and then follows in general by taking colimits.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is very convenient and not at all how tensor products work for ordinary modules!
        By contrast, in <m>\Mod_R</m>, there is a canonical morphism
        <me>
          \prod_I R \otimes_R \prod_J R \to \prod_{I \times J} R
        </me>
        but this is not an isomorphism when both index sets are infinite.
      </p>
    <definition>
      <p>
        We say that <m>M \in \Mod_{R_\solid}</m> is <term>flat</term> if <m>M \otimes_{R_\solid} \bullet</m> is an exact functor on <m>\Mod_{R_\solid}</m>.
        By <xref ref="eq-solid-product-on-one-free"/>, any product <m>\prod_I M_i</m> of flat solid modules is again flat.
        By contrast, for ordinary modules this holds if and only if the base ring is coherent (<xref ref="bib-Stacks"/>, tag 05CZ).
      </p>
    </definition>
    <remark xml:id="rem-topological-completion">
      <p>
        This failure of flatness for localizations echoes similar failures elsewhere in formal/analytic geometry.
        For instance, the completion of a non-noetherian ring with respect to a finitely generated ideal need not be flat
        (<xref ref="bib-Stacks"/>, tag 0AL8); for similar reasons, a completed rational localization of a completed Huber ring
        need not be flat. Even in cases where flatness holds (e.g., for localizations of classical affinoid algebras), this is only
        a statement about the exactness of <em>algebraic</em> tensor products, not the <em>topological</em> tensor products that are
        more relevant. One way around this is to work systematically with <term>derived categories</term> of modules; we will take up this point later in the course.
      </p>
      <p>
        As a preview for how these topics will be linked, let us make an observation about the ring <m>\ZZ_p</m> of <term><m>p</m>-adic integers</term>.
        It is classically defined as the completion of the ring <m>\ZZ</m> with respect to the ideal <m>(p)</m>.
        In symbols, we can write <m>\ZZ_p</m> as the kernel of the map
        <me>
          \prod_{n \in \NN} \ZZ/p^n \ZZ \to \prod_{n \in \NN} \ZZ/p^n \ZZ, \quad (a_n)_{n \in \NN} \mapsto (a_n - a_{n+1} \pmod{p^n})_{n \in \NN}.
        </me>
        In the notation of <xref ref="exa-base-extension-not-flat"/>, it is natural to define a solid analogue <m>\ZZ_{p \solid}</m> by taking the corresponding 
        kernel out of <m>M</m> (i.e., the <q>solid completion</q> of <m>\ZZ</m> along <m>(p)</m>). 
        This can be viewed as a ring object in the category of solid <m>\ZZ</m>-modules; we can then define the module category
        <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_{p \solid}}</m> by taking solid <m>\ZZ</m>-modules <m>M</m> equipped with a ring homomorphism <m>\ZZ_{p \solid} \to \iHom_{\ZZ_{\solid}}(M,M)</m>.
        This is <em>not</em> the same thing as <m>\Mod_{{\ZZ_p}_\solid}</m>, the category of solid <m>R</m>-modules for <m>R = \ZZ_p</m>, which treats <m>\ZZ_p</m> as a discrete ring;
        instead, we are taking the <m>p</m>-adic topology into account in the module structure, so we are getting something more akin to <q>topological <m>\ZZ_p</m>-modules</q>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <remark>
      <p>
        When applying <xref ref="rem-liquefaction-kills-ext1"/>, one must make sure that <m>R_0^{\triangleright}</m> is itself not a derived ring!
        This will not be an issue when constructing examples directly, but comes up when we try to make constructions like rational localizations
        (<xref ref="rem-localization-is-underived"/>).
      </p>
    </remark>
      <p>
        Unfortunately, this favorable situation does not persist when <m>A</m> is a more general solid analytic ring.
        In that case, we should treat the Koszul complex itself as the derived version of the rational localization,
        as in <xref ref="exa-Koszul-complex-not-acyclic"/>. In order to work with this systematically, 
        one needs to consider some sort of derived rings, which we will not do for the moment.
        We will however write <m>A\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle^L</m> in case we need to indicate the derived localization.
      </p>
      <p>
        To keep track of this issue, we will say that <m>A</m> is <term>locally underived</term>
        if every rational localization of <m>A</m> coincides with the corresponding derived localization.
      </p>
    <example xml:id="exa-Koszul-complex-not-acyclic">
      <p>
        Following <xref ref="exa-base-extension-not-flat"/>, 
        take <m>M := \coker(\underline{\ZZ} \to \prod_n \underline{\ZZ/p^n \ZZ}) \in \CAb_\solid</m>;
        take <m>A^{\triangleright} := \underline{\ZZ} \oplus M</m> with <m>M^2 = 0</m>;
        and take <m>f=1, g=p</m>. Then the derived rational localization of <m>A^{\triangleright}</m> with parameters <m>f,g</m>
        can be interpreted as 
        <me>
          \underline{\ZZ}\langle \tfrac{1}{p} \rangle \otimes_\solid^L A^{\triangleright}
          = \underline{\ZZ}[\tfrac{1}{p}] \otimes_\solid^L A^{\triangleright}, 
        </me>
        which has a copy of <m>\underline{\ZZ}[1/p]</m> placed in degree <m>-1</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
    <remark xml:id="rem-localization-is-underived">
      <p>
        The formula in <xref ref="eq-formula-rational-localization"/> does not change if we interpret everything as an operation of derived rings.
        This breaks down into three separate statements.
        <ul>
          <li>
            The condensed ring <m>A^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{g}]</m> is resolved by the Koszul complex associated to <m>1-gU \in A^{\triangleright}[U]</m>.
            This amounts to saying that multiplication by <m>1-gU</m> is injective on <m>A^{\triangleright}[U]</m>, which is evident because
             <m>A^{\triangleright}[U]</m> injects into <m>A^{\triangleright}\llbracket U \rrbracket</m> and multiplication by <m>1-gU</m> is an isomorphism there.
          </li>
          <li>
            The liquefaction of <m>A^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{g}][T_1,\dots,T_n]</m> at <m>\{T_1,\dots,T_n\}</m> is underived.
            This follows from <xref ref="rem-liquefaction-kills-ext1"/>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The final quotient is resolved by the Koszul complex associated to <m>T_1 - \tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,T_n - \tfrac{f_n}{g} \in A^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{g}][T_1,\dots,T_n]_{\liquid \{T_1,\dots,T_n\}}</m>.
            By interpreting the construction as a series of localizations of <m>B^{\triangleright} := A^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{g}]</m>, we can treat one parameter at a time;
            we then have to check that for <m>h_i := \tfrac{f_i}{g}</m>,
            <me>
              0 \to B^{\triangleright}[T_i]_{\liquid T_i} \stackrel{\times T_i-h_i}{\to} B^{\triangleright}[T_i]_{\liquid T_i} \to B^{\triangleright}[T_i]_{\liquid T_i}/(T_i-h_i) \to 0
            </me>
            is exact at the left. That is, for <m>M = B^{\triangleright} \in \Mod_B</m>, we must check that multiplication by <m>T_i-h_i</m>
            is injective on <m>M \otimes_{B^{\triangleright}} B^{\triangleright}[T_i]_{\liquid T_i}</m>.
            Note that <m>B^{\triangleright}[T_i]_{\liquid T_i}</m> is projective in <m>\Mod_B</m>,
            so we may exploit the exact sequence
            <me>
              0 \to \ker(B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{h_i}]) \to B^{\triangleright} \to \ima(B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{h_i}]) \to 0
            </me>
            to reduce to checking the claim for <m>M = \ker(B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{h_i}])</m>
            and <m>M = \ima(B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{h_i}])</m>.
            The former holds by writing <m>M = \colim_n M_n</m> with <m>M_n := \ker(B^{\triangleright} \stackrel{\times h_i^n}{\to} B^{\triangleright})</m>,
            then noting that multiplication by <m>T_i^n</m> on <m>M_n \otimes_{B^{\triangleright}} B^{\triangleright}[T_i]_{\liquid T_i}</m>
            (which is obviously injective)
            coincides with multiplication by <m>T_i^n - h_i^n</m> and hence factors through multiplication by <m>T_i-h_i</m>.
            The latter holds because multiplication by <m>T_i-h_i</m> and <m>1-h_i^{-1}T_i</m> on <m>M = \ima(B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{h_i}])</m> have the same kernel,
            and the latter is injective as in the first step.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        From the previous discussion, we see that for any morphism <m>A \to B</m> of solid analytic rings,
        <m>B^{\triangleright} \otimes^L_A A^{\triangleright}\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,\tfrac{f_n}{g} \rangle</m> is underived.
      </p>
