    <p>
      Let us identify a key situation where the localizations are all underived.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem-discrete-localizations-are-underived">
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be a solid analytic ring whose underlying ring <m>A^{\triangleright}</m> is discrete.
        Then every rational localization of <m>A</m> is underived with discrete underlying ring: for <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g</m> generating the unit ideal,
        we have <m>A^{\triangleright}[T_1,\dots,T_n]_{\liquid T_1,\dots,T_n} = A^{\triangleright}[T_1,\dots,T_n]</m> and this is resolved by the Koszul complex
        as in <xref ref="rem-localization-is-underived"/>. In particular, <m>A</m> is locally underived.
      </p>
      <p>
        We can use this to formulate <q>universal</q> versions of various statements about sheafiness
        in which no derived localizations are involved.
        For example, the universal case of <xref ref="lem-sheafy-exact-sequence"/> is
        <me>
          A = \underline{\ZZ}[a,b,f,g]/(af+bg-1)
        </me>.
        See <xref ref="thm-solid-sheafy-universal"/> for a similar use of this point of view.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-solid-sheafy-universal">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For the ring 
          <me>
            A := \underline{\ZZ}[a_1,\dots,a_n,f_1,\dots,f_n]/(a_1f_1 + \cdots + a_nf_n - 1)
          </me>,
          let <m>A_i</m> denote the rational localization of <m>A</m> corresponding to the parameters <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,f_i</m>.
          Then 
          <me>
            0 \to A^{\triangleright} \to \bigoplus_i A_i^{\triangleright} \to \bigoplus_{i\lt j} A_i^{\triangleright} \otimes_A A_j^{\triangleright} \to \cdots
          </me>
          is an exact sequence in <m>\Mod_A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          This follows from <xref ref="prop-standard-binary-coverings-Huber"/> and <xref ref="lem-sheafy-exact-sequence"/>
          (because <xref ref="rem-discrete-localizations-are-underived"/> guarantees that all rational localizations that intervene are underived).
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
    <remark>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="thm-solid-sheafy-universal"/>,
        tensoring along any morphism <m>A \to B</m> of solid analytic rings yields a zero object in the derived category <m>D(\Mod_A)</m>.
        If in fact <m>B_i := B \otimes_A^L A_i</m> is underived for all <m>i</m>, then 
        <me>
          0 \to B^{\triangleright} \to \bigoplus_i B_i^{\triangleright} \to \bigoplus_{i\lt j} B_i^{\triangleright} \otimes_A B_j^{\triangleright} \to \cdots
        </me>
        is an exact sequence in <m>\Mod_B</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
        
        Recall that an analytic ring <m>A</m> consists of a pair <m>(A^{\triangleright}, \Mod_A)</m> where <m>A^{\triangleright}</m> is some underlying condensed ring
        and <m>\Mod_A</m> is a full subcategory of <m>\Mod_{A^{\triangleright}}</m> subject to some restrictions (<xref ref="def-analytic-ring"/>).
        Define the category <m>\QCoh</m> of <term>analytic quasicoherent sheaves</term> to consist of pairs <m>(A, M)</m> where <m>A \in \AnRing</m>, <m>M \in \Mod_A</m>;
        with a morphism <m>(B, N) \to (A, M)</m> consisting of a morphism <m>A \to B</m> in <m>\AnRing</m> and an isomorphism <m>M \otimes_A B \cong N</m>.
        This gives a category fibered in groupoids over <m>\AnRing^{\op}</m>.
    <remark xml:id="rem-no-flatness">
      <p>
        With notation as in <xref ref="prop-solid-rational-localization"/>, the base extension functor <m>\bullet \otimes_A B \colon \Mod_A \to \Mod_B</m>
        is almost never exact (even when <m>A</m> is a Huber pair, or even sheafy), because of examples as in <xref ref="exa-base-extension-not-flat"/>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since we want to think of <m>\Mod_A</m> as the category of quasicoherent sheaves on <m>\Spa A</m>, this means that we cannot treat the category of quasicoherent sheaves
        on solid analytic rings as a sheaf for any reasonable topology, even the one generated by standard binary coverings.
        However, what is true is that the <em>derived</em> category of quasicoherent sheaves is a sheaf for this topology, and even some richer topologies,
        <em>provided</em> that we understand derived categories using the language of <term>stable <m>\infty</m>-categories</term>. 
        More on this in a moment!
      </p>
    </remark>

        As noted in <xref ref="rem-no-flatness"/>, we cannot prove an analogue of <xref ref="lem-descent-standard-covering"/>
        for <m>\Mod_A</m> instead of its derived category because the base extension functors are not exact.
        On the other hand, working at the derived category provides some technical advantages apart from resolving this issue,
        as one can see by comparing the proof of Zariski descent for quasicoherent sheaves on schemes versus for the derived categories:
        in the derived setting essential surjectivity is formal, whereas in the underived setting it requires some nontrivial argument.
      </p>
      <p>
        The tradeoff is that one has to be careful about what a derived category is; the classical definition,
        where one takes the homotopy category of complexes and inverts quasi-isomorphisms (see for example <xref ref="bib-Stacks"/>, tag 05RR), 
        is too crude because it loses the information of
        <em>how</em> two complexes are related; specifically, this obstructs the formation of limits and colimits.
        The language of <m>\infty</m>-categories is better suited to retain this extra information,
        and it is in this language that one can actually formulate a statement to the effect that <m>D(\QCoh)</m> is a sheaf for the adic topology.
      </p>
      <p>
        To make the issue more explicit, note that 
              <p>
        By contrast, we do not get a glueing statement in fixed amplitude: for example in the equivalence
        <men xml:id="eq-glueing-equivalence-qcoh">
          \calD(\Mod_A) \to \calD(\Mod_{A \left\langle f/g \right\rangle}) \times_{\calD(\Mod_{A \left\langle f/g, g/f \right\rangle})} \calD(\Mod_{A \left\langle g/f \right\rangle})
        </men>
        glueing complexes supported in
        degrees <m>\leq 0</m> in general only yields a complex supported in degrees <m>\leq 1</m>.
        We will revisit this point in <xref ref="thm-pseudocoherent-descent-with-amplitude"/>.
      </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-covering-by-local">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A \to A_1, A \to A_2</m> be a standard binary covering of a Huber ring <m>A</m>.
          Let <m>h\colon A^m \to A^n</m> be a morphism in <m>\Mod_A</m> such that the induced maps <m>h_1\colon A_1^m \to A_1^n</m>, <m>h_2\colon A_2^m \to A_2^n</m> are surjective.
          Then <m>h</m> is surjective.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Since the covering is defined by a pair of elements <m>f,g \in A</m> which generate the unit ideal,
          the image of the map <m>\Spec(A_1 \oplus A_2) \to \Spec(A)</m> includes all maximal ideals.
          The claim then follows from Nakayama's lemma applied after taking global sections.
        </p>
      </proof>
