            <definition xml:id="def-absolutely-flat-rings">
      <p>
        A morphism <m>A \to B</m> in <m>\Ring</m> is <term>absolutely flat</term> (or <term>weakly étale</term>) if <m>A \to B</m>
        and <m>B \otimes_A B \to B</m> are both flat. In particular, <m>B \otimes_A^L B \to B</m> is flat.
      </p>
      <p>
        For instance, any étale morphism is absolutely flat.
        Also, any colimit of absolutely flat morphisms is absolutely flat;
        in particular, localization at any multiplicative subset (which need not be of finite type) is absolutely flat.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>pro-étale topology</term> on <m>\Ring^{\op}</m>, as considered by Bhatt<ndash/>Scholze <xref ref="bib-Bhatt-Scholze-proetale"/>,
        is the topology generated by finite disjoint unions and morphisms which are both faithfully flat and absolutely flat.
        This includes more coverings than the Zariski topology and the étale topology, but fewer than the fpqc topology.
      </p>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Modeling <xref ref="def-absolutely-flat-rings"/> in analytic rings, we obtain the following definition.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <p>
        A morphism <m>A \to B</m> of analytic rings is <term>absolutely flat</term>
        if <m>A \to B</m> and <m>B \to B \otimes_A B</m> are both flat.
        Any idempotent morphism is absolutely flat. In addition, for any finite family <m>\{A \to A_i\}</m> of absolutely flat morphisms,
        <m>A \to B = \bigoplus_i A_i</m> is absolutely flat.
      </p>
    </definition>
    <definition>
      <p>
        The <term>pro-étale topology</term> on <m>\AnRing^{\op}</m> is generated by finite families of absolutely flat morphisms <m>\{\AnSpec A_i \to \AnSpec A\}_{i \in I}</m>
        such that for <m>B := \bigoplus_i A_i</m>, the <term>Cech<ndash/>Alexander complex</term>
        <men xml:id="eq-proetale-topology">
          0 \to A^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright} \otimes^L_A B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright} \otimes^L_A B^{\triangleright} \otimes^L_A B^{\triangleright} \to \cdots
        </men>
        to be exact. For example, any covering for the idempotent topology is also a covering for the pro-étale topology.
      </p>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <p>
        <xref ref="thm-gaga-discrete"/> suggests some common aspects of different flavors of GAGA theorems.
        Notably, we must distinguish between quasicoherent sheaves on the scheme <m>\PP^1_A</m>, which are all colimits of coherent sheaves,
        and quasicoherent sheaves on the analytic space <m>\PP^1_{\underline{A}}</m>, which are built out of condensed <m>\underline{A}</m>-modules
        and therefore need not be colimits of coherent sheaves.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <lemma xml:id="cor-analytic-Huber-exact-seq">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a solid analytic ring. Then the sequences
          <md>
            <mrow>
              0 \to A[T] \to A\langle T \rangle \oplus A\langle T^{-1} \rangle[T] \to A \langle T^{\pm} \rangle \to 0
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              0 \to A[T^{\pm}] \to A\langle T \rangle[T^{-1}] \oplus A\langle T^{-1} \rangle[T] \to A\langle T^{\pm} \rangle \to 0
            </mrow>
          </md>
          are exact.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Apply <xref ref="eq-sheafy-exact-sequence"/> to the rings <m>A[T], A[T^{\pm}]</m> and the elements <m>f=T, g=1</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-gaga-P1-Huber">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any solid analytic ring <m>A</m>, the restriction functor
          <me>
            \Mod_{A[T]} \times_{\Mod_{A[T^{\pm}]}} \Mod_{A[T^{-1}]} \to
            \Mod_{A \langle T \rangle} \times_{\Mod_{A\langle T^{\pm} \rangle}} \Mod_{A\langle T^{-1} \rangle}
          </me>
          is an equivalence of categories, and the restriction functor
          <me>
            \calD(\Mod_{A[T]}) \times_{\calD(\Mod_{A[T^{\pm}]})} \calD(\Mod_{A[T^{-1}]}) \to
            \calD(\Mod_{A \langle T \rangle}) \times_{\calD(\Mod_{A\langle T^{\pm} \rangle})} \calD(\Mod_{A\langle T^{-1} \rangle})
          </me>
          is an equivalence of stable <m>\infty</m>-categories.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We treat the second case, the first case being similar.
          By applying <xref ref="cor-analytic-Huber-exact-seq"/>, 
          we get equivalences
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \calD(\Mod_{A[T]}) \to \calD(\Mod_{A\langle T \rangle}) \times_{\calD(\Mod_{A \langle T,T^{-1} \rangle})} \calD(\Mod_{A \langle T^{-1} \rangle[T]})
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \calD(\Mod_{A[T^{-1}]}) \to \calD(\Mod_{A\langle T \rangle}[T^{-1}]) \times_{\calD(\Mod_{A \langle T,T^{-1} \rangle})} \calD(\Mod_{A \langle T^{-1} \rangle})
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \calD(\Mod_{A[T^{\pm}]}) \to \calD(\Mod_{A\langle T \rangle}[T^{-1}]) \times_{\calD(\Mod_{A \langle T,T^{-1} \rangle})} \calD(\Mod_{A \langle T^{-1} \rangle[T]})
            </mrow>
          </md>.
          Combining these yields the claim.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
