    <lemma>
      <title>Generic Schwartz lemma</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an arbitrary analytic ring and fix <m>S \in \Prof</m>.
          Then for any trace class morphism <m>f\colon A[\underline{S}] \to A[\underline{S}]</m>,
          <m>\cone(f-1)</m> is isomorphic in <m>\calD(\Mod_{A})</m> to
          a complex of the form <m>A^{\triangleright n}[-1] \to A^{n}[0]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We may assume <m>S</m> is infinite as otherwise there is nothing to check.
          Define a map <m>g\colon P \to \ZZ[\underline{S}]</m> as in <xref ref="def-construct-map-P-to-monoid"/>.
          Using <xref ref="lem-diagram-p-to-bd-S"/> as in the proof of <xref ref="lem-identify-solidification-of-free"/>,
          we obtain an identification <m>P \otimes_{\ZZ} A \cong A[\underline{S}]</m>. 
          As in the proof of <xref ref="lem-trace-class"/>, we may lift to a setting where <m>A^{\triangleright}</m> is represented by a topological ring
          which is liquid with respect to some topologically nilpotent unit <m>q</m>.
          Now using the fact that <m>A^{\circ \circ}</m> is open in <m>A^{\triangleright}(*)</m>,
          we can imitate the proof of <xref ref="lem-trace-class"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
