    <proposition xml:id="prop-solid-rational-localization">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A^{\triangleright}</m> be a solid condensed ring and choose <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g \in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m>.
          Then there is a homomorphism <m>A^{\triangleright} \to A^{\triangleright} \left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle</m> of solid condensed rings which is initial for the properties that:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <m>g</m> is invertible in <m>A^{\triangleright} \left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle</m>;
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>f_1/g, \dots, f_n/g</m> are power-bounded in <m>A^{\triangleright} \left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle</m>.
            </li>
          </ul>
          Moreover, for any solid analytic ring <m>A</m> with underlying ring <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>,
          the map <m>A^{\triangleright} \to A^{\triangleright} \left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle</m> upgrades uniquely to a 
          morphism <m>A \to A\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle</m> of solid analytic rings 
          (that is, we are taking <m>A\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle^\triangleright = A^{\triangleright}\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle</m>)
          which is initial for the additional property that 
          every object of <m>\Mod_{A\left\langle f_1/g, \dots, f_n/g\right\rangle}</m> is <m>\left\{\tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,\tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\}</m>-liquid.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          For the first assertion, take
          <men xml:id="eq-formula-rational-localization">
            A^{\triangleright} \left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle := 
            \frac{A^{\triangleright}[T_1,\dots,T_n]_{\liquid T_1,\dots,T_n}}{(f_1-gT_1,\dots,f_n-gT_n)}
          </men>.
          <men>
            A^{\triangleright} \left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g}\right\rangle := 
            \frac{A^{\triangleright}\left[ \tfrac{1}{g} \right][T_1,\dots,T_n]_{\liquid \{T_1,\dots,T_n\}}}{(f_1-gT_1,\dots,f_n-gT_n)}
          </men>.
          For the second assertion, it suffices to note that the construction in <xref ref="eq-formula-rational-localization"/> starts with the object
          <m>A^{\triangleright} \in \Mod_A</m> and then progresses through a sequence of steps that maintain membership in <m>\Mod_A</m>:
          adjunction of <m>\tfrac{1}{g}</m> (which can be viewed as passage to the free module <m>A^{\triangleright}[T]</m>
          and then quotienting by the ideal <m>1-gT</m>); adjunction of the variables <m>T_1,\dots,T_n</m>; liquefaction
          with respect to <
          m>T_1,\dots,T_n</m>; and quotienting by the ideal <m>(f_1-gT_1,\dots,f_n-gT_n)</m>. 
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
