    <example xml:id="eq-liquefaction-idempotent">
      <p>
        Equip <m>\ZZ[q]</m> with the discrete topology. Then the morphism <m>\underline{\ZZ[q]} \to \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q}</m>
        gives rise to an idempotent morphism of discrete analytic rings.
      </p>
      <p>
        To see that <m>\underline{\ZZ[q]} \to \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q}</m> is flat, we may argue as in <xref ref="eq-sequence-space-idempotent"/>:
        form the exact sequence
        <me>
          0 \to \underline{\ZZ[q]} \otimes \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q} \stackrel{\times (q \otimes 1 - 1 \otimes q)}{\to} 
          \underline{\ZZ[q]} \otimes \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q} \to \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q} \to 0
        </me>,
        then observe that for any <m>M \in \Mod_{\underline{\ZZ[q]}}</m>, <m>M \otimes_{\underline{\ZZ[q]}} \underline{\ZZ[q]} \otimes \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q} \cong 
        M \otimes \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q}</m>
        injects into <m>M \otimes (\underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q} \oplus \prod_{n \lt 0} \ZZ q^{n})</m>
        on which multiplication by <m>q \otimes 1 - 1 \otimes q = (1 \otimes q)(q \otimes q^{-1} - 1)</m> is an isomorphism.
      </p>
      <p>
        To see that <m>\underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q} \otimes_{\underline{\ZZ[q]}} \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q} \cong \underline{\ZZ[q]}</m>,
        use the explicit description of <m>\underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q}</m> given in <xref ref="prop-initial-analytic"/> to see that 
        <me>
          (\underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q} \otimes \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q})_{\liquid \{q \otimes 1, 1 \otimes q\}}/(q \otimes 1 - 1 \otimes q) 
          \cong \underline{\ZZ[q]}_{\liquid q}
        </me>.
      </p>
    </example>
    <remark xml:id="rem-liquefaction-idempotent">
      <p>
        By base extension from <xref ref="eq-liquefaction-idempotent"/>, 
        we deduce that for any analytic ring <m>A</m> and any <m>q \in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m>,
        the morphism 
        <me>
          A \to (A^{\triangleright}_{\liquid q}, \Mod_{A^{\triangleright}_{\liquid q}} \times_{\Mod_{A^{\triangleright}}} \Mod_A)
        </me> 
        is idempotent.
        This applies in particular for <m>q=1</m>, in which case we may write <m>A^{\triangleright}_{\solid}</m> for <m>A^{\triangleright}_{\liquid q}</m>.
        However, as per <xref ref="rem-idempotent-module-category"/>, if we replace the module category with its subcategory of <m>q</m>-liquid objects
        then we only get a weakly idempotent morphism.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <example xml:id="exa-rational-localization-is-idempotent-general">
      <p>
        We reprise <xref ref="exa-rational-localization-is-idempotent"/>, but now allowing <m>A</m> be a general (not necessarily solid) analytic ring.
        We may factor <m>A^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}</m> as 
        <me>
          A^{\triangleright} \to A^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{g}] \to A^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{g}]_{\liquid f_1/g} \to \cdots \to A^{\triangleright}[\tfrac{1}{g}]_{\liquid f_1/g,\dots,f_n/g}
        </me>.
        Combining <xref ref="eq-Zariski-localization-idempotent"/> with <xref ref="eq-liquefaction-idempotent"/>,
