    <definition>
      <p>
        For <m>R</m> a commutative ring, an <term>abstract norm function</term> on <m>R</m> is a function <m>N \colon |\PP^1_R| \to [0, \infty]</m>
        subject to the following conditions.
        <ul>
          <li>
            For <m>0_R \colon \Spec R \to \PP^1_R</m> the zero section, <m>N \circ 0_R = 0</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            For <m>r\colon \PP^1_R \to \PP^1_R</m> the inversion map, 
            <m>N \circ |r| = 1/N</m>.
            (Combined with the first point, this implies that <m>N\circ 1_R = 1</m> and <m>N\circ \infty_R = \infty</m>.)
          </li>
          <li>
            For <m>X \subseteq \PP^1_R \times_R \PP^1_R \times_R \PP^1_R</m> the Zariski closure of the graph of the multiplication map
            <m>\mu\colon \AAA^1_R \times_R \AAA^1_R \to \AAA^1_R</m>,
            <m>(N \times N \times N)|_X \colon X \to [0,\infty]^3</m> factors through the closure of the graph of the multiplication map
            <m>[0,\infty) \times [0,\infty) \to [0, \infty)</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            For <m>X \subseteq \PP^1_R \times_R \PP^1_R \times_R \PP^1_R</m> the Zariski closure of the graph of the addition map
            <m>\sigma\colon \AAA^1_R \times_R \AAA^1_R \to \AAA^1_R</m>,
            <m>(N \times N \times N)|_X \colon X \to [0,\infty]^3</m> factors through the closure of the graph of the addition map
            <m>[0,\infty) \times [0,\infty) \to [0, \infty)</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <p>
        When <m>R</m> is a field, the data of an abstract norm function on <m>R</m> is the same as the data of a multiplicative norm on <m>R</m>.
        In general, since we have not imposed any structural restriction on <m>N</m>, the whole definition degenerates: the data is just that of
        a multiplicative norm on each residue field of <m>R</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We would like to refine this definition by upgrading <m>N</m> to a <q>geometric</q> map <m>\PP^1_R \to [0, \infty]</m>,
        but it is not obvious how to embed both source and target into a common category where such a map could live.
        We will eventually consider the category of <term>analytic stacks</term> where this takes place;
        for the moment we will work with <m>\Fun(\AnRing^{\op}, \Set)</m>, but eventually we will want to specify a topology on <m>\AnRing</m> and consider only the sheaves for this topology.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a solid analytic ring. Then for any <m>M \in \Mod_{A}</m>,
          <me>
            M \otimes^L_A A^{\triangleright} \langle T \rangle \cong \iHom_{\underline{\ZZ}}(P, M)
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By rewriting 
          <me>
            M \otimes^L_A A^{\triangleright} \langle T \rangle 
            \cong M \otimes^L_A A^{\triangleright} \otimes^L_{\underline{\ZZ}\solid} \underline{\ZZ} \langle T \rangle
          </me>
          we reduce to the case <m>A = (\underline{\ZZ}, \Mod_{\underline{\ZZ} \solid})</m>.
          For <m>M = A = \underline{\ZZ}</m>,
          we may apply <xref ref="rem-adjoin-top-nilpotent"/> to transfer to the case
          <m>M = A = \underline{\ZZ((q))}</m> and then apply the discussion in <xref ref="def-solid-Tate"/>.
          For general <m>M</m>, we may replace <m>A</m> with the square-zero extension <m>M \oplus A</m> and repeat the argument.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a solid analytic ring.
          Then for any <m>M \in \Mod_A</m>, <m>M \otimes_A A^{\triangleright} \langle T \rangle</m> is <m>T</m>-liquid.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T"/>, <m>M \otimes_A A^{\triangleright} \langle T \rangle \cong \iHom_{\CAb}(P, M)</m>.
          The claim is then that <m>\Delta_T^*</m> is a bijection on 
          <me>
            \iHom_{CAb}(P, \iHom_{\CAb}(P, M)) = \iHom_{\CAb}(P \otimes P, M)
          </me>;
          as this statement makes no reference to the <m>A</m>-module structure on <m>M</m>, we may check it for <m>A = \underline{\ZZ}</m>.
          In that case, we formally reduce first to the case <m>M = \prod_I \underline{\ZZ}</m>, then by compatibility with products to the case
          <m>M = \underline{\ZZ}</m>; unwinding, this just comes down to the tautology that <m>A^{\triangleright}[T]_{\liquid T}</m> is
          <m>T</m>-liquid.
        </p>
        <p>
          See also <xref ref="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid-general"/> for an alternate proof that applies to a somewhat more general setting.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A \to B</m> be a rational localization of solid analytic rings corresponding to parameters
          <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g\in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m> which generate the unit ideal.
          Assume further that <m>A</m> admits a topologically nilpotent unit.
          Then 
          <me>
            \Mod_B = \Mod_{B^{\triangleright}} \times_{\Mod_{A^{\triangleright}}} \Mod_A
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We may check this after first replacing <m>A</m> with <m>A[1/g]</m>, in which case we reduce to the case where the parameters defining
          the rational localization have the form <m>h,1</m>. In this case we may apply <xref ref="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid"/> 
          to conclude.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>
    <definition>
      <p>
        We would like to define a <term>quasicoherent sheaf</term> on <m>\AnRing^{\op}</m> to be a sheaf locally
        for the adic topology of the form <m>M \otimes_A B</m> for some <m>M \in \Mod_A</m>.
        However, this tensor product is in general derived.
      </p>
      <p>
        Define a <term>quasicoherent sheaf</term> on <m>\AnSpec A</m> to be a sheaf of condensed abelian groups on <m>\AnRing^{\op}_{\solid/A}</m>
        equipped with the structure of an <m>\calO</m>-module (for <m>\calO</m> the structure sheaf, as in <xref ref="thm-solid-sheafy"/>)
        which is locally associated to a module. That is, for <m>\calF</m> to be quasicoherent, there must exist a covering family of loose rational localizations
        <m>\{A \to B_i\}</m> such that <m>\calF|_{\AnSpec B_i} \in \Mod_{B_i}</m> for each <m>i</m>.
        Let <m>\LQCoh_A</m> be the category of loose quasicoherent sheaves on <m>\AnSpec A</m>. 
      </p>
    </definition>
    <p>
      To prove that <m>\Mod_A \to \LQCoh_A</m> is essentially surjective, it is convenient to first prove glueing in the derived category.
      Before getting too far into the categorical weeds, let us formulate the main glueing lemma for a two-term covering.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-module-to-sheaf">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a solid analytic ring and fix <m>M \in A</m>.
          Let <m>\calC</m> be the subcategory of <m>\AnRing^{\op}_{\solid/A}</m> consisting of loose rational
          localizations of <m>A</m>. Then the functor
          <m>B \mapsto M \otimes^L_A B^{\triangleright}</m>
          (here using <xref ref="thm-localization-is-flat"/> to see that the tensor product is underived)
          is a sheaf <m>\tilde{M}</m> of condensed abelian groups on <m>\calC</m> for the loose adic topology.
          Moreover, <m>H^i(\calC, \tilde{M}) = 0</m> for <m>i \gt 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          The claim follows from <xref ref="thm-solid-sheafy"/> by tensoring with <m>M</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
      <p>
        Recall that by <xref ref="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid"/>,
        the base extension functor <m>\bullet \otimes_A A^{\triangleright}[T]_{\liquid T}</m> carries <m>\Mod_A</m>
        into <m>\Mod_{A\langle T \rangle}</m>, without needing to liquefy with respect to <m>T</m>.
        This means that we can pull back quasicoherent sheaves from <m>\PP^1_A</m> to <m>\PP^1_{A \solid}</m>.
      </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T-general">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an analytic ring which is liquid with respect to some unit <m>q \in A^{\circ}</m>
          and which admits a topologically nilpotent unit (not necessarily equal to <m>q</m>).
          Then for any <m>M \in \Mod_{A}</m>, we have a functorial isomorphism
          <men xml:id="eq-tensor-with-liquid-T-general">
            M \otimes^L_A A^{\triangleright} \langle T \rangle^\dagger_q \cong \colim_m \iHom_{\underline{\ZZ}}(P_m, M)
          </men>
          where for each positive integer <m>m</m>, <m>P_m</m> denotes a copy of the sequence space <m>P</m>
          and the transition maps are induced by
          <men xml:id="eq-tensor-with-liquid-T-transition">
            P_{m+1} \to P_m, \qquad [n] \mapsto q^{\lfloor n/m \rfloor - \lfloor n/(m+1) \rfloor} [n]
          </men>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          For <m>M = A</m>, this follows from <xref ref="lem-dagger-as-liquefaction"/>.
          In the general case, replace <m>A</m> with the square-zero extension <m>A \oplus M</m> and apply the previous case.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <p>
      We must now address a subtlety that arose previously in the solid case
      (<xref ref="cor-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid"/>):
      the definition of a rational localization includes a choice of module category
      which in principle could obstruct the construction of quasicoherent sheaves.
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid-general">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an analytic ring which is liquid with respect to some unit <m>q \in A^{\circ}</m>.
          Then for any <m>M \in \Mod_A</m>,
          <m>M \otimes_A A^{\triangleright} \langle T \rangle^\dagger_q</m> is <m>T^{m}q</m>-liquid for every positive integer <m>m</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We check the case <m>m=1</m>, as the general case reduces to it by adjoining <m>q^{1/m}</m> to <m>A</m>.
          By <xref ref="rem-adjoin-top-nilpotent-liquid"/>, we may further assume that <m>A</m> admits a topologically nilpotent unit.
          By <xref ref="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T-general"/>, <m>M \otimes_A A^{\triangleright} \langle T \rangle \cong \colim_m \iHom_{\CAb}(P_m, M)</m>.
          The claim is then that <m>\Delta_{Tq}^*</m> is a bijection on 
          <me>
            \colim_m \iHom_{CAb}(P, \iHom_{\CAb}(P_m, M)) = \colim_m \iHom_{\CAb}(P \otimes P_m, M)
          </me>.
          Now note that for each <m>m</m>, <m>1-\Delta_{Tq}</m> acts on <m>P \otimes P_m</m> via the product of shifts in <em>opposite</em> directions,
          so <m>\Delta_{Tq}</m> admits the inverse <m>\sum_n (1-\Delta_{Tq})^n</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <corollary xml:id="cor-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid-general">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an analytic ring which is liquid with respect to some unit <m>q \in A^{\circ}</m>.
          Choose <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g \in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m> generating the unit ideal and set
          <me>
            B^\dagger := A \left \langle \frac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \frac{f_n}{g} \right\rangle^\dagger_q
          </me>.
          Then
          <me>
            \Mod_{B^\dagger} = \Mod_{B^{\dagger \triangleright}} \times_{\Mod_{A^{\triangleright}}} \Mod_A
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Using <xref ref="lem-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid-general"/>, this follows as in the proof of <xref ref="cor-tensor-with-liquid-T-is-liquid"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>
          
