          <xref ref="lem-submodule-free-over-PID"/> again, <m>\overline{Q}</m> is again a free <m>\ZZ</m>-module,
          so the target <m>\bigoplus_J \ZZ</m> admits a splitting with <m>\overline{Q}</m> as a direct summand.
          This now transposes to a decomposition of the source <m>\prod_J \ZZ_\solid</m> as a product into two factors,
          each itself a product of copies of <m>\ZZ_\solid</m>, and we can replace the source with one of these factors
          (discarding the dual of <m>\overline{Q}</m>) in such a way that we now have a new sequence as in <xref ref="eq-sandwich-free-module"/>, but
          now <m>Q</m> is a torsion <m>\ZZ</m>-module.
        <p>
          Let <m>D</m> be the divisible closure of the image of <m>h</m> within <m>\bigoplus_J \ZZ</m>.
          By <xref ref="lem-submodule-free-over-PID"/>, <m>D</m> is also a free <m>\ZZ</m>-module.
          By <xref ref="prop-solid-internal-hom"/>, the dual of <m>D</m> is a product of copies of <m>\ZZ_\solid</m>
          through which <m>g</m> factors, as then does the map <m>\prod_J \ZZ_\solid \to M</m>
          since <m>M \to \prod_I \ZZ_\solid</m> is injective.
          We can thus replace the source <m>\prod_J \ZZ_\solid</m> with this product;
          at this point, <m>h</m> is still injective but now <m>Q := \coker(h)</m> is torsion.
        </p>
        <p>
          Now dualizing the sequence
          <men xml:id="eq-length-1-resolution-of-solid">
            0 \to \bigoplus_I \ZZ \stackrel{h}{\to} \bigoplus_J \ZZ \to Q \to 0
          </men>
          and invoking <xref ref="lem-hom-from-torsion-vanishes"/> yields
          <men xml:id="eq-hom-from-torsion-sequence">
            0 = \iHom_{\ZZ_\solid}(Q_\solid, \ZZ_\solid) \to \prod_J \ZZ_\solid \stackrel{g}{\to} \prod_I \ZZ_\solid
          </men>.
          At this point, we know that in <xref ref="eq-sandwich-free-module"/>, the first map is surjective, the second map is injective,
          and the composition is also injective. Consequently the first map <m>\prod_I \ZZ_\solid \to M</m> is an isomorphism, proving the claim.
        </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-prod-Z-is-free">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any set <m>I</m>, <m>\prod_I \ZZ</m> is a free <m>\ZZ</m>-module.
          (Note that here we are taking the product in the category of discrete <m>\ZZ</m>-modules, not in the solid category.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Choose a set of elements <m>B</m> in <m>\prod_I \ZZ</m> lifting a basis of the <m>\FF_2</m>-vector space
          <m>\prod_I \ZZ/2\ZZ</m>. Then any relation among elements of <m>B</m> is infinitely 2-divisible and hence
          vanishes; we deduce that the map <m>\bigoplus_B \ZZ \to \prod_I \ZZ</m> is an isomorphism.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-split-off-free-sub">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>Q</m> be a <m>\ZZ</m>-module. Then <m>Q</m> admits a splitting as <m>Q' \oplus Q''</m>
          such that <m>Q'</m> is free and <m>\Hom_{\ZZ}(Q'', \ZZ) = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Set <m>K := \Hom_{\ZZ}(Q, \ZZ)</m>.
          We then have a natural evaluation map <m>Q \to \prod_K \ZZ</m>; let <m>Q'</m> be its image.
          By <xref ref="lem-prod-Z-is-free"/>, the target <m>\prod_K \ZZ</m> is a free <m>\ZZ</m>-module, as then by
          <xref ref="lem-submodule-free-over-PID"/> is <m>Q'</m>; we can thus split 
          <m>Q</m> as the sum of <m>Q'</m> plus a complementary summand <m>Q''</m>.
          From the split exact sequence
          <me>
            0 \to Q' \to Q \to Q'' \to 0
          </me>
          we obtain the split exact sequence
          <me>
            0 \to \Hom_\ZZ(Q'', \ZZ) \to K \to \Hom_\ZZ(Q', \ZZ) \to 0
          </me>
          in which the right map is also injective (because by construction any morphism <m>Q \to \ZZ</m>
          factors through <m>Q'</m>). Consequently, <m>\Hom_{\ZZ}(Q'', \ZZ) = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
      <p>
        By the same token, if <m>Q,Q'</m> are two <m>\ZZ</m>-modules
        with <m>|Q|, |Q'| \leq \kappa</m> and <m>\Hom_{\ZZ}(Q, \ZZ) = \Hom_{\ZZ}(Q', \ZZ) = 0</m>, then
        any morphism <m>Q \to Q'</m> that induces an isomorphism 
        <m>\iExt^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(Q'_\solid, \ZZ_\solid) \to \iExt^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(Q_\solid, \ZZ_\solid)</m>
        is itself an isomorphism.
        To begin with, if one of <m>Q</m> or <m>Q'</m> is zero, then the other is both free
        (by <xref ref="prop-Whitehead-for-solid"/>) and has no nonzero maps to <m>\ZZ</m>, and hence must be zero.
        Next, <m>\iExt^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(\bullet, \ZZ_\solid)</m> is right exact because
        <m>iExt^2_{\ZZ_\solid}(\bullet, \ZZ_\solid)</m> is identically zero, so we may apply the previous case to
        <m>\coker(Q \to Q')</m> to deduce that <m>Q \to Q'</m> is surjective.
        Finally, by <xref ref="lem-hom-from-torsion-vanishes"/> we have
        <m>\iHom_{\ZZ_\solid}(Q'_\solid, \ZZ_\solid) = 0</m>, so we may apply the first case to
        <m>\ker(Q \to Q')</m> to deduce that <m>Q \to Q'</m> is injective.
      </p>
        <p>  
          By <xref ref="cor-length-1-resolution-of-solid"/>, we can find an exact sequence of the form
          <me>
            0 \to \prod_J \ZZ_\solid \stackrel{g}{\to} \prod_I \ZZ_\solid \to N \to 0
          </me>.
          As in the proof of <xref ref="lem-subobject-of-finitely-generated"/>
          (applied to the image of <m>g</m>),
          after removing a summand of <m>N</m> of the form <m>\prod_K \ZZ_\solid</m>,
          we can ensure that the dual morphism <m>h\colon \bigoplus_I \ZZ \to \bigoplus_J \ZZ</m> of <m>g</m>
          is injective and that its cokernel <m>Q</m> satisfies <m>\Hom_\ZZ(Q, \ZZ) = 0</m>.
          At this point, the sequence <xref ref="eq-hom-from-torsion-sequence"/> continues
          <me>
            0 \to \prod_J \ZZ_\solid \stackrel{g}{\to} \prod_I \ZZ_\solid \to \iExt^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(Q_\solid, \ZZ_\solid) \to \iExt^1_{\ZZ_\solid}\left(\prod_J \ZZ_\solid, \ZZ_\solid\right) = 0
          </me>
          where the last term vanishes because <m>\prod_J \ZZ_\solid</m> is projective in <m>\Mod_{\ZZ_\solid}</m>.
          We conclude that our original <m>N</m> splits as a product of copies of <m>\ZZ_\solid</m> plus <m>\iExt^1_{\ZZ_\solid}(Q_\solid, \ZZ_\solid)</m>.
        </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-divisible-closure-finitely-generated">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>M</m> be a finitely generated <m>\ZZ</m>-submodule of <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ</m>.
          Then the divisible closure of <m>M</m> in <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ</m> is also finitely generated.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Choose a basis of <m>M</m> and record the elements of this basis as a semi-infinite matrix of integers
          (with finitely many columns and countably many rows). We can then perform elementary row and column operations
          on this matrix without changing the isomorphism class of either <m>M</m> or its divisible closure.
          In particular, we can put the matrix into Hermite normal form, from which the claim is evident.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-countable-sub-of-product-is-free">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>M</m> be a <m>\ZZ</m>-submodule of <m>\prod_I \ZZ</m> for some index set <m>I</m>
          with <m>|M| \leq \aleph_0</m>.
          Then <m>M</m> is free.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By hypothesis, we can find a surjection <m>\bigoplus_J \ZZ \to M</m> with <m>|J| \leq \aleph_0</m>.
          There is nothing to check if <m>J</m> is finite, as then we can project from <m>I</m> onto some finite index
          set and then apply <xref ref="lem-submodule-free-over-PID"/>.
          We may thus assume that <m>J = \NN</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Let <m>F_n</m> be the divisible closure in <m>M</m> of the image of <m>\bigoplus_{\{0,\dots,n-1\}} \ZZ</m>.
          Since <m>F_n</m> is contained in the divisible closure of the image of <m>\bigoplus_{\{0,\dots,n-1\}} \ZZ</m>
          in <m>\prod_I \ZZ</m>, which by <xref ref="lem-divisible-closure-finitely-generated"/> is finitely generated,
          so then is <m>F_n</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For each <m>n \gt 0</m>, <m>F_n/F_{n-1}</m> is finitely generated (by the previous paragraph)
          and torsion-free (since <m>M/F_{n-1}</m> is by construction), hence free.
          for each <m>n \gt 0</m>.
          In particular, we can choose a splitting <m>F_n \cong F_{n-1} \oplus (F_n/F_{n-1})</m>.
          Combining these splittings yields a coherent sequence of isomorphisms
          <me>
            F_n \cong F_0 \oplus (F_1/F_0) \oplus \cdots \oplus (F_n/F_{n-1})
          </me>,
          and taking colimits yields an isomorphism
          <me>
            M \cong F_0 \oplus (F_1/F_0) \oplus \cdots
          </me>
          which shows that <m>M</m> is free.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <remark>
      <p>
        The cardinality condition in <xref ref="lem-countable-sub-of-product-is-free"/>
        is needed because the product <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ</m> is <em>not</em> a free <m>\ZZ</m>-module.
        To see this, suppose to the contrary that <m>\prod_\NN \ZZ \cong \bigoplus_I \ZZ</m> for some <m>I</m>,
        necessarily with <m>|I| = 2^{\aleph_0}</m>.
        The image of <m>\bigoplus_\NN \ZZ \to \prod_\NN \ZZ</m> would then be contained in <m>\bigoplus_J \ZZ</m>
        for some countable subset <m>J</m> of <m>I</m> (namely, the union of the supports of the images of each generator
        of <m>\bigoplus_\NN \ZZ</m> in <m>\bigoplus_I \ZZ</m>). This would in turn imply that 
        the divisible subgroup of <m>\left( \prod_\NN \ZZ \right) / \left( \bigoplus_\NN \ZZ \right)</m>
        is countable (as this quotient would be contained in the product of the torsion-free group <m>\bigoplus_{I \setminus J} \ZZ</m>
        with a countable group), but this is manifestly false: the map
        <me>
          \left( \prod_\NN \ZZ \right) / \left( \bigoplus_\NN \ZZ \right) \to \left( \prod_\NN \ZZ \right) / \left( \bigoplus_\NN \ZZ \right),
          \qquad (a_n)_n \mapsto (n! a_n)_n
        </me>
        is injective, its domain is uncountable, and its image is contained in the divisible subgroup of the codomain.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-split-off-free-sub">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>Q</m> be a <m>\ZZ</m>-module with <m>|Q| \leq \aleph_0</m>. 
          Then <m>Q</m> admits a splitting as <m>Q' \oplus Q''</m>
          such that <m>Q'</m> is free and <m>\Hom_{\ZZ}(Q'', \ZZ) = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Set <m>K := \Hom_{\ZZ}(Q, \ZZ)</m>.
          We then have a natural evaluation map <m>Q \to \prod_K \ZZ</m>; let <m>Q'</m> be its image,
          which by <xref ref="lem-countable-sub-of-product-is-free"/> is free. We can then split 
          <m>Q</m> as the sum of <m>Q'</m> plus a complementary summand <m>Q''</m>.
          From the split exact sequence
          <me>
            0 \to Q' \to Q \to Q'' \to 0
          </me>
          we obtain the split exact sequence
          <me>
            0 \to \Hom_\ZZ(Q'', \ZZ) \to K \to \Hom_\ZZ(Q', \ZZ) \to 0
          </me>
          in which the right map is also injective (because by construction any morphism <m>Q \to \ZZ</m>
          factors through <m>Q'</m>). Consequently, <m>\Hom_{\ZZ}(Q'', \ZZ) = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <p>
      We have the following analogue of <xref ref="lem-submodule-free-over-PID"/>.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="lem-subobject-of-finitely-generated">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any <m>I</m> with <m>|I| \leq \aleph_0</m>,
          any finitely generated subobject of <m>\prod_I \ZZ_\solid</m> is itself a product of copies of <m>\ZZ_\solid</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>M</m> be a finitely generated subobject of <m>\prod_I \ZZ_\solid</m>. By definition, it sits in a sequence
          <men xml:id="eq-sandwich-free-module">
            \prod_J \ZZ_\solid \to M \to \prod_I \ZZ_\solid
          </men>
          where the first map is surjective and the second map is injective.
