          We then have <m>(h_g \oplus \lambda) \circ (\Delta_{f} \oplus \Delta_f) = \Delta_{fg} \circ (h_g \oplus \lambda)</m>.
          Since <m>(\Delta_f \oplus \Delta_f)^*</m> is an isomorphism on <m>\iHom_{\CAb}(P \oplus P, M)</m> and <m>h_g \oplus \lambda</m>
          is a split surjection,
          tracing around the square as in <xref ref="lem-replace-bounded-with-P-solid"/>
          shows that <m>\Delta_{fg}^*</m> is also an isomorphism.
        </p>
    <proposition xml:id="cor-liquid-top-nilpotent-unit">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a condensed commutative ring.
          Let <m>\varpi_1,\varpi_2 \in R(*)</m> be two topologically nilpotent units.
          Then <m>\Mod_{R \liquid \varpi_1} = \Mod_{R \liquid \varpi_2}</m>;
          consequently, both of these equal <m>\Mod_{R \liquid S}</m> where <m>S</m> is the entire set of topologically nilpotent elements of <m>R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By symmetry it suffices to check that <m>\Mod_{R \liquid \varpi_1} \subseteq \Mod_{R \liquid \varpi_2}</m>.
          Since <m>\varpi_2</m> is topologically nilpotent, there exists a positive integer <m>n</m> such that <m>\varpi_3 := \varpi_2^n \varpi_1^{-1}</m>
          is also topologically nilpotent. By <xref ref="rem-f-solidification-versus-fg"/>
          we have <m>\Mod_{R \liquid \varpi_1} \subseteq \Mod_{R \liquid \varpi_1 \varpi_3} = \Mod_{R \liquid \varpi_2^n}</m>;
          by <xref ref="lem-f-solidification-versus-fn"/>, the latter equals <m>\Mod_{R \liquid \varpi_2}</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-localization-is-flat">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a solid analytic ring and choose <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g \in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m>
          (not necessarily generating the unit ideal). 
          Then <m>A\to A\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,\tfrac{f_n}{g} \right\rangle</m>
          is flat, that is, base extension along this morphism defines an exact functor <m>\Mod_{A} \to \Mod_{A\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,\tfrac{f_n}{g} \rangle}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Since the construction of <m>A\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,\tfrac{f_n}{g} \right\rangle</m>
          factors through <m>A[1/g]</m>, we first note that <m>A \to A[1/g]</m> is flat
          (either by <xref ref="lem-flat-mult-f"/> or simply by writing 
          <m>A^{\triangleright}[1/g] = \colim (A^{\triangleright} \stackrel{\times g}{\to} A^{\triangleright} \stackrel{\times g}{\to} \cdots)</m>).
          We may thus assume hereafter that <m>g</m> is invertible, or even that <m>g=1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We then note that <m>A\left\langle f_1,\dots,f_n\right\rangle</m> can be factored as a sequence of rational localizations with parameters <m>f_i,1</m>
          for <m>i=1,\dots,n</m>. We thus reduce to the case <m>n = 1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Finally, we apply <xref ref="lem-flat-mult-f-v2"/> to see that the sequence
          <me>
            0 \to A^{\triangleright}\langle T \rangle \stackrel{\times T-f}{\to} A^{\triangleright}\langle T \rangle 
            \to A^{\triangleright} \langle f \rangle \to 0
          </me>
          remains exact upon tensoring with any <m>M \in \Mod_A</m>. 
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
      <p>        
        While <xref ref="thm-localization-is-flat"/> is analogous to the flatness of Zariski localizations in commutative algebra,
        it has no real counterpart elsewhere in analytic geometry.
        For instance, it is not true that rational localizations of Huber rings are always flat even in the algebraic sense;
        in cases where this does hold (e.g., for classical affinoid algebras) one still does not get an exact base extension functor on complete
        topological modules. The latter is perhaps not so surprising because taking a tensor product of topological modules in the condensed setting does
        not necessarily return a topological module; this is the same issue arising in <xref ref="rem-rational-subspace-derived"/>.
      </p>
