  <subsection>
    <title>The flat topology</title>
    <p>
      We compare the previous discussion with the following definition in algebraic geometry.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <p>
        A morphism <m>A \to B</m> of analytic rings is <term>faithfully flat</term> if <m>A \to B</m> is flat and
        <m>\Mod_A \to \Mod_B</m> is faithful (every nonzero object has nonzero image).
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>flat topology</term> (or <term>fpqc topology</term>)
        on <m>\AnRing^{\op}</m> is generated by finite families of flat morphisms <m>\{\AnSpec A_i \to \AnSpec A\}_{i \in I}</m>
        such that <m>A \to B := \bigoplus_i A_i</m> is faithfully flat.
        For example, any covering for the idempotent topology is also a covering for the flat topology.
      </p>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <p>
        For any analytic ring <m>A</m>, <m>A \to A[T]</m> is a covering for the flat topology.
        For <m>A</m> solid, by <xref ref="exa-rational-localization-is-idempotent"/>, 
        <m>A[T] \to A[T]_{\liquid T}</m> is flat, so
        <m>A \to A[T]_{\liquid T}</m> is also a covering for the flat topology.
      </p>
    </example>
    <example>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be an analytic ring. Fix a finite étale morphism <m>A^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}</m>;
        then <m>B^{\triangleright}</m> is finite projective as an <m>A^{\triangleright}</m>-module, so <m>B^{\triangleright} \in \Mod_A</m>.
        We promote <m>B^{\triangleright}</m> to an analytic ring <m>B</m> by taking <m>\Mod_B</m> to be the <m>B^{\triangleright}</m>-module 
        objects in <m>\Mod_A</m>.
        Then <m>A \to B</m> is flat.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now suppose that <m>A^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright}</m> is also faithfully flat.
        Then <m>A \to B</m> is faithfully flat.
      </p>
    </example>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-idempotent-covering-is-flat">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Any covering for the idempotent topology on <m>\AnRing^{\op}</m> is also a covering for the flat topology.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          For <m>M \in \Mod_A</m> nonzero, tensoring with <xref ref="eq-idempotent-topology"/> shows that 
          <m>M \otimes_A B^{\triangleright}</m> is nonzero.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-faithfully-flat-cech-alexander">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A flat morphism <m>A \to B</m> of analytic rings is faithfully flat if and only if the <term>Čech<ndash/>Alexander complex</term>
          <men xml:id="eq-proetale-topology">
            0 \to A^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright} \otimes^L_A B^{\triangleright} \to B^{\triangleright} \otimes^L_A B^{\triangleright} \otimes^L_A B^{\triangleright} \to \cdots
          </men>
          is exact. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          If <m>A \to B</m> is faithfully flat, then we can deduce the exactness of <xref ref="eq-proetale-topology"/> from the corresponding sequence
          with <m>A \to B</m> replaced by <m>B \to B \otimes_A B</m>. The latter is formally true because <m>B \to B \otimes_A B</m> is split by the
          multiplicative map.
        </p>
        <p>
          Conversely, if <xref ref="eq-proetale-topology"/> is exact, then for <m>M \in \Mod_A</m> nonzero, tensoring with <xref ref="eq-proetale-topology"/>
          shows that <m>M \otimes_A B^{\triangleright}</m> is nonzero.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-sheaf-absolutely-flat">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A \to B</m> be a faithfully flat morphism of analytic rings. 
          Then <m>\calD(\Mod_A)</m> is isomorphic (via base extension) to the limit of the diagram
          <me>
            \Mod_B \to \Mod_{B \otimes_A B} \rightrightarrows \Mod_{B \otimes_A B \otimes_A B} \to \cdots
          </me>.
          Moreover, <m>\calD(\Mod_A)</m> is isomorphic (via base extension) to the limit of the diagram
          <me>
            \calD(\Mod_B) \to \calD(\Mod_{B \otimes_A B}) \rightrightarrows \calD(\Mod_{B \otimes_A B \otimes_A B}) \to \cdots
          </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          It suffices to prove the second statement.
          The limit can be interpreted as the derived <m>\infty</m>-category of modules over the simplicial analytic ring 
          <me>
            F \colon [0] \mapsto B, [1] \mapsto B \otimes B, \dots
          </me>.
          Again, the base extension functor from <m>A</m> to <m>F</m> admits a right adjoint (restriction of scalars),
          and using <xref ref="eq-proetale-topology"/> we see that the unit of the adjunction is an equivalence on <m>\calD(\Mod_A)</m>.
          The counit is an equivalence for formal reasons: it can be interpreted as base extension from <m>B</m> to <m>B \otimes_A B</m>
          and then back to <m>B</m> via the multiplication map.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-localization-is-flat">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a solid analytic ring and choose <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g \in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m>
          (not necessarily generating the unit ideal). 
          Then <m>A\to A\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,\tfrac{f_n}{g} \right\rangle</m>
          is flat, that is, base extension along this morphism defines an exact functor <m>\Mod_{A} \to \Mod_{A\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,\tfrac{f_n}{g} \rangle}</m>.
        </p>
