    <corollary xml:id="rem-localization-is-underived">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a solid condensed ring and suppose that <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g \in R(*)</m> generate the unit ideal.
          Then <m>R\left\langle \tfrac{f_1}{g},\dots,\tfrac{f_n}{g} \right\rangle</m>
          is resolved by the Koszul complex over <m>R[1/g]\langle T_1,\dots,T_n\rangle</m> 
          defined by the elements <m>f_i - g T_i</m> for <m>i=1,\dots,n</m>.
          Moreover, if <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g</m> generate the unit ideal, then we may replace <m>R[1/g]</m> with <m>R</m> with the same result.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="lem-sheafy-exact-sequence-v2"/>, 
          we may check the exactness of the augmented Koszul complex locally on the terms of a standard binary covering
          defined by parameters of the form <m>f,1</m> or <m>f,1-f</m>. By this plus <xref ref="prop-standard-binary-coverings-Huber"/>,
          we are reduced to working locally with respect to a refinement of the covering defined by <xref ref="lem-standard-rational-covering"/> using the parameters
          <m>f_1,\dots,f_n,g</m>. If we end up in the situation where <m>\tfrac{f_1}{g}, \dots, \tfrac{f_n}{g} \in R^{\circ}</m>, then the Koszul complex
