    <p>
      We apply the explicit formula for derived solidification <xref ref="eq-derived-solidification"/> in the following manner.
    </p>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-top-group-no-derived-solidification">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any sequential topological abelian group <m>M</m>, the derived solidification of <m>\underline{M}</m> is concentrated in degree <m>0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="rem-express-solidification-using-cof"/>, this is equivalent to the assertion that
          <me>
            \iHom_{\CAb}(\coker(\Delta)/\underline{\ZZ}, \underline{M}) = 0
          </me>.
          This in turn is equivalent to the assertion that <m>S \in \Prof</m>,
          <me>
            \Hom_{\CAb}(\coker(\Delta)/\underline{\ZZ} \otimes \ZZ[\underline{S}], \underline{M}) = 0
          </me>.
          To check this, note that a morphism <m>\coker(\Delta)/\underline{\ZZ} \otimes \ZZ[\underline{S}] \to \underline{M}</m>
          corresponds to a morphism <m>\ZZ[\underline{\NN_\infty \times S}] \to \underline{M}</m>
          whose restrictions to <m>\ZZ[\underline{\{\infty\} \times S}]</m>
          and to the preimage of <m>(\ima(\Delta) \oplus \ZZ) \otimes \ZZ[\underline{S}]</m>
          vanish.
          Since <m>\prod_\NN \underline{\ZZ}</m> is represented by a sequential topological abelian group,
          a morphism <m>\ZZ[\underline{\NN_\infty \times S}] \to \underline{M}</m> corresponds to a continuous map <m>f</m>
          from <m>\NN_\infty \times S</m> to <m>M</m>;
          we may thus check the claimed vanishing in the case where <m>S</m> is a singleton.
        </p>
        <p>
          At this point, the condition that the restriction to <m>\ZZ[\underline{\{\infty\}}]</m> vanishes implies that
          <m>f(\infty) = 0</m>.
          The condition that the restriction to <m>\ima(\Delta)</m> vanishies implies that <m>f(n) = f(n+1)</m>
          for all <m>n \in \NN</m>. By continuity, we deduce that <m>f</m> is identically zero.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
    <remark>
      <p>
        Since <m>P</m> is represented by a sequential topological abelian group (<xref ref="def-internally-projective-object"/>),
        <xref ref="lem-top-group-no-derived-solidification"/> implies that the underived and derived solidifications of <m>P</m> coincide.
        This can also be seen from <xref ref="rem-express-solidification-using-cof"/>: it suffices to check that
        <m>\iExt^1_{\CAb}(P, M) = 0</m> for any <m>M \in \CAb_\solid</m>, 
        but since any extension of <m>M</m> by <m>P</m> is again solid (by <xref ref="prop-solid-category"/>) we may apply <xref ref="prop-internally-projective"/> and adjunction to see that any such extension splits.
        (See <xref ref="rem-liquefaction-kills-ext1"/> for the same observation in a more general setting.)
      </p>
    </remark>
        If <m>M</m> is concentrated in degrees <m>[a,b]</m>, then by <xref ref="eq-resolve-cofinite-mod-Z"/> 
        its derived solidification is concentrated in degrees <m>[a-1,b]</m>.
          the promotion to the derived coalescence follows from <xref ref="rem-liquefaction-kills-ext1"/>.
      <p>
        which means that if <m>M</m> is concentrated in degrees <m>[a,b]</m>, then its derived <m>f</m>-coalescence is concentrated in degrees <m>[a-1,b]</m>.
        In particular, for <m>M \in \Mod_R</m> the derived <m>f</m>-coalescence is concentrated in degrees <m>-1</m> and <m>0</m>,
        with the term in degree <m>-1</m> being <m>\iHom_R(\coker(\Delta_f)/R, M)</m>;
        this makes it clear that this term is nonzero for instance when <m>M = \coker(\Delta_f)/R</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The existence of the resolution <xref ref="eq-resolve-coker-mod-R-liquefaction"/> has the following important consequence for the construction of analytic rings.
        Let <m>R_0 = (R_0^{\triangleright}, \Mod_{R_0})</m> be an analytic ring,
        choose <m>f \in R_0(*)</m>, and let <m>\Mod_{R_1} := \Mod_{R_0 \liquid f}</m> be the full subcategory of <m>f</m>-coalescent objects in <m>\Mod_{R_0}</m>.
        Then the underived <m>f</m>-coalescence <m>R_1^{\triangleright}</m> of <m>R_0^{\triangleright}</m> has the property that for any <m>M \in \Mod_{R_1}</m>,
        <m>\Ext^1_{R_0^{\triangleright}}(R_1^\triangleright, M) = 0</m>: for any exact sequence in <m>\Mod_{R_0^{\triangleright}}</m> of the form
        <me>
          0 \to M \to M' \to R_1^{\triangleright} \to 0
        </me>
        we have <m>M' \in \Mod_{R_1}</m> by <xref ref="prop-liquefaction"/>, so any splitting of the pullback sequence
        <me>
          0 \to M \to M' \times_{R_1^{\triangleright}} R_0^{\triangleright} \to R_0^{\triangleright} \to 0
        </me>
        (which exists because <m>R_0^{\triangleright}</m> is projective as a module over itself)
        extends by adjunction to a splitting of the original sequence.
        By replacing <m>M</m> with <m>\iHom_{R_0^{\triangleright}}(R_0^{\triangleright} \otimes \ZZ[\underline{S}], M)</m>,
        we formally upgrade this conclusion to assert that <m>\iExt^1_{R_0^{\triangleright}}(R_1^\triangleright, M) = 0</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        From this, we see that <m>R_1^{\triangleright}</m> is also the derived <m>f</m>-coalescence of <m>R_0^{\triangleright}</m>.
        That is, the issue
        raised in <xref ref="rem-pre-analytic-to-analytic"/> does not arise in this context,
        and so <m>R_1 = (R_1^{\triangleright}, \Mod_{R_1})</m> is itself an analytic ring. 
      </p>
      <p>
        By similar logic, starting from the fact that <m>P</m> is internally projective in <m>\CAb</m> (<xref ref="prop-internally-projective"/>),
        we may see that the derived <m>f</m>-coalescence of <m>P \otimes R_0^{\triangleright}</m> equals <m>P \otimes R_1^{\triangleright}</m> placed in degree 0,
        which is again internally projective in <m>\Mod_{R_1}</m>.
      </p>
    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be a sheafy solid analytic ring and choose <m>f,g \in A^{\triangleright}(*)</m> generating the unit ideal.
          Then the base extension functor
          <men xml:id="eq-derived-base-extension-functor-loose">
            D(\Mod_A) \to D(\Mod_{A \left\langle f/g \right\rangle}) \times_{D(\Mod_{A \left\langle f/g, g/f \right\rangle})} D(\Mod_{A \left\langle g/f \right\rangle})
          </men>
          is an equivalence of categories.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Each of the functors from <m>D(\Mod_A)</m> to one of the other categories has a right adjoint (restriction of scalars), so the same is true of
          the base extension. It thus remains to establish that the unit and the counit of this adjunction are equivalences.
          To simplify notation, let us rewrite <xref ref="eq-derived-base-extension-functor"/> as
          <me>
            D(\Mod_A) \to D(\Mod_{A_1}) \times_{D(\Mod_{A_{12}})} D(\Mod_{A_{2}})
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          To check the unit, note that by <xref ref="lem-sheafy-exact-sequence"/>, the sequence <xref ref="eq-sheafy-exact-sequence"/> is exact.
          For any <m>M \in D(\Mod_A)</m>, we may take the (derived) tensor product of this sequence with <m>M</m> to obtain a morphism from the mapping cone of
          <me>
            M \otimes_A A_1 \oplus M \otimes_A A_2 \to M \otimes_A A_{12}
          </me>
          to <m>M</m> in <m>D(\Mod_A)</m> which inverts the adjunction.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the counit, we first apply the universal property of localization to see that the multiplication maps
          <men xml:id="eq-double-base-extension">
            A_{S_1} \otimes^L_A A_{S_2} \to A_{S_1 \cup S_2}
          </men>
          are isomorphisms for any subsets <m>S_1, S_2</m> of <m>\{1,2\}</m>. Using these isomorphisms, we see that if we start with <m>M_i \in \Mod_{A_i}</m>
          and ismoorphisms <m>M_i \otimes_{A_i} A_{12} \cong M_{12}</m>, the counit is a map from <m>(M_1 \times_{M_{12}} M_2) \otimes^L_A A_i \in \Mod_{A_i}</m>
          to <m>M_i \otimes^L_A A_i</m> and then to <m>M_i</m>, and using <xref ref="eq-double-base-extension"/> we can produce inverses to both factors.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>
      <p>
        By analogy with <xref ref="def-loose-rational-localization"/>, we define also the 
        associated <term>loose dagger localization</term> by taking the same morphism of underlying rings,
        but with the induced module category.
        This will be an idempotent morphism.
      </p>
        <p>
          We then apply the previous case and <xref ref="prop-standard-binary-coverings-Huber"/>
          to work locally on <m>A</m>, and thereby reduce to the case where (without loss of generality) <m>A = A^{\triangleright}\left\langle \tfrac{f}{g} \right\rangle^\dagger_q</m>.
          In that case, <m>A^{\triangleright} \left\langle \tfrac{g}{f} \right\rangle^\dagger_q = A^{\triangleright}\left\langle \tfrac{f}{g}, \tfrac{g}{f} \right\rangle^\dagger_q</m>
          and the sequence in question is split exact.
        </p>
          This further reduces to mapping <m>\underline{\ZZ}[q^{\pm}]\langle U \rangle[T]/(T^m q - U)</m> to <m>R[T]_{\liquid T^{m+1} q}</m>.
          To do this, we first reduce to the universal case <m>R = \underline{\ZZ((r))}[q^{\pm}]</m>;
          then apply <xref ref="lem-liquefaction-is-Tate-algebra"/> to equate <m>R \langle T \rangle</m> with <m>R[T]_{\liquid T}</m>;
          and finally apply <xref ref="eq-dagger-transition"/> to obtain
          <me>
            (T^m q)^n = (T^{m+1} q)^{\lfloor \frac{nm}{m+1} \rfloor} T^{nm-(m+1)\lfloor \frac{nm}{m+1}\rfloor} q^{n - \lfloor \frac{nm}{m+1}\rfloor}
          </me>
          and note that the exponent of <m>T</m> is at most <m>m</m> while the exponent of <m>q</m> is at least <m>\tfrac{n}{m+1} - 1</m>.
        <p>
          
          To produce the map from left to right, we first observe that the target belongs to <m>\Mod_{R[T]\liquid q}</m>;
          it thus suffices to map <m>\underline{\ZZ}[q^{\pm}]\langle T \rangle^\dagger_q</m> to <m>\colim_m R[T]_{\liquid T^m q}</m>.
          By hypothesis, <m>R</m> is an algebra over <m>R = \underline{\ZZ((r))}[q^{\pm}]</m>;
          by <xref ref="lem-liquefaction-is-Tate-algebra"/> we may equate <m>\underline{\ZZ((r))}[q^{\pm}] \langle U \rangle</m> with <m>\underline{\ZZ((r))}[q^{\pm}][U]_{\liquid U}</m>.
          We thus obtain a map from <m>\underline{\ZZ}[q^{\pm}]\langle U \rangle[T]/(T^m q - U)</m> to <m>R[T]_{\liquid T^m q}</m>.
          To produce the map from right to left, we show that <m>R[T]_{\liquid T^m q}</m> maps to
          <m>R \otimes_{\liquid q} \underline{\ZZ}[q^{\pm}]\langle U \rangle[T]/(T^{m+1} q - U)</m>.
          Since the claim is universal in <m>R</m>, it suffices to work at the level of global sections:
          a global section of <m>R[T]_{\liquid T^m q}</m> can be written as <m>\sum_n r_n T^n</m> with <m>r_n \in R(*)</m>
          such that <m>r_n q^{-\lfloor \frac{n}{m} \rfloor}</m> is a null sequence.
          By rewriting this as <m>r_n q^{-\lfloor \frac{n}{m+1} \rfloor}</m> times <m>q^{\lfloor \frac{n}{m} \rfloor - \lfloor \frac{n}{m+1} \rfloor}</m>
          and noting that the exponent is at least <m>\tfrac{n}{m(m+1)} - 1</m>, we see that the sum can be formed in 
          <m>R \otimes_{\liquid q} \underline{\ZZ}[q^{\pm}]\langle U \rangle[T]/(T^{m+1} q - U)</m>.
        </p>
